,Not Recommended,240760,12196444,"Posted: 22 September, 2014",all,Sandwichman,"Tough, painful, and worthy of ragequitting. And no, I'm not talking about the game being difficult.I'm talking about:A skill system which is brokenAttributes which mean nothingclunky game mechanicsthe AI taking multiple turns in a row with unlimited SP and near 100% hit ratestatistics shattering weapon jams and missesutterly no roleplaying experiencea tactical game where you only need one tacticand the list goes on.In fact here's one example, you have an assault rifle, there's no one around you, your enemy is in the ""sweet spot"" as in not too close, not too far. Your gauge shows that you have a 70% chance to hit. and you miss. not just once, but 5 times in a row. or more. As I posted on another person's review in a comment: ""I really think the devs need to go back to hs and take some statistics, cause the odds of missing so many shots in a row when it's 70% or more ""to hit""... is beyond stupid. Think about it, a 3 in 7 chance to miss five times in a row is 3 in 16,807 (or a 0.01% chance of happening). But it happens so frequently it's more like the reverse 70% chance to miss. But then again, even the odds of missing 5 times in a row would still be 7 in 243 (or a 2.88% chance of happening).. which is still absurd. And yet the game does this for most people I've heard talking about it.""This is a common experience. and it just keeps going. enemies almost always hit, have twice the range of your snipers (from even the beginning missions), your guns jam at least once a battle (when each gun's jam rate is 5% or less), and so on.I just about rage quit the other night because the immersion in the story is so awful it just breaks you out of the game by destroying the suspension of disbelief. You get ""badass"" rangers telling you that they are the team that goes in and kills other rangers, and get told stories of other rangers making tough choices and coming out on top. Then you try and do anything contrary to the story and you're done. You do one thing wrong and an entire town aggros against you. And no there's no charisma stat that calms people down, no speechcraft skill which says ""slow down compadre,"" no kill the leader and stop the aggro, it's just one bugged out exchange where you might as well reboot to your last save (if you're lucky enough to not trust the game to make backup saves from time to time) or you kill the entire town/area and (as some have said) you cannot complete the game. I personally don't have any experience with that, as I'm only 20 something hours in, but come-on, this is ridiculous.It's not about a complex storyline or making a game that's tough, it's sloppy game design mixed with poor story writing. And it's bad programming, on numerous occasions I've experienced a plethora of bugs including one where the camera won't pan, but for some reason I can move the sun in the sky (yeah, no joke). And the stuff that is programmed ""right"" is just poor. There is no choice in the game other than linear save town A and you have problems with town B for the game, or save town B and have problems with town A down the line. Then there's the AI and battles, at first it's new and fun and interesting. Then it's just a poorly designed squad tactics game where the enemies do the same thing every time and so do you. I really only employed one strategy in 20+ hours of gameplay. set up 2 short range fighters, set up 2 assault rifle fighters and 1 sniper and the rest of the game is a cake walk. It's not fun, it's repetitive.Another problem is the ""fans"" who jump on any topic you make or post and immediately say it's your fault the game is bad, or that you're not reading all the text, or that you are doing combat wrong, or... blah blah blah, but the game is as I've stated above, one-dimensional, clunky, broken and worthy of ragequitting. This last bit about the fans can't be the dev's fault, but the hype about this being the game everyone wanted Fallout 3 to be, is like gasoline on a fire, it just burns hotter and less controlled. If you take an objective look at the game, you'll see the same stuff that I and many others have pointed out. At least with the story stuff I'm willing to agree to disagree, as I can see how if you don't think about the story or complete failure on the roleplaying aspect of the game then you've got yourself a repetitive one-tactic game where you make choices like a train choosing which railroad track to take, sure you can take the long way around, but the end result is the same, you're still stuck on the tracks.I really really really wanted to like this and I just can't. Maybe I'll give it another try down the road, but I've got a sour taste in my mouth right now."
76561198123627918,Recommended,240760,8898213,"Posted: 29 January, 2014",all,rwh1981,"I want to start this off with this comment; the game is currently in beta.  That said, I am sure you have read that multiple times now through the various posts.  So, where to start?Straight up, this game will not be for everyone.  No, that does not mean it is a bad game.  Far from it, honestly.   I bought the deluxe edition on a whim.  Wanted to try something new.  I saw it was beta, so I started playing with that mindset.  That, so far, is the biggest thing.  It is not a complete game, so some things do not work, or work as expected.  Now, keeping that in mind, if you get this game, the end product in my opinion, will be phenomenal!I am playing on max settings, looks and runs smooth, no issues.  I DO NOT have a top of the line machine.  Voices thus far are good, dialogue is great.  Combat mechanics are good.  Story so far seems great as well.To make this easier, if you take the time to read this, I will break it down.  Again, keep in mind this is a BETA.  Not a beta you may be used to, more like end of the line alpha.  Point being, a WORK IN PROGRESS.PROS:--Character customization and looks in game.--Story is great thus far.--Combat will be great once game is complete.--Graphics / audio / and interface thus far are all great.--Gameplay is sweet.  I said it may not be for everyone because combat is tactical / turn.  So, think back old school with X-Com.  I love that part of it, personal opinion.--Combat animations / effects are sweet.--Choice and consequence are a part of this game.  You save someone from drowning, his parents offer him to you as an added party member if you want.  Plenty of characters to change up the party.--Different skills are used for different things.  Obviously, ha ha.  Those chances to use the skills on a frequent basis are not persistent in other games.  There are a lot of opportunity to use each skill you have in your party.  I like that.--A TON of interactions within the world.  Be it digging stuff up, repairing gadgets, even down to repairing toasters, ha ha!  (definitely have someone in your party that can repair them, because you never know what's stored in one!)--Completed game will hands down be great.CONS:--Loading a save will often change the portrait of your character(s) if they are created from scratch.  A minor annoyance, unless you get into combat, then you have to go by name.  Or, if you made a guy and your portrait is now a gal.--Combat, sometimes, can be a bit.. Interesting.  You have a sniper, that has 0.0% chance of hitting a target.  That same target now moves behind cover, and you now have an 80.00% chance to hit.--Combat again, some enemies have ridiculous move / attacks.  They will move across the screen, attack you twice, then move again... BETA, remember.  It will frustrate / annoy you though, ha ha.--Make sure you get a dedicated surgeon / healer.  I roamed around for a bit trying to find someone that could heal my wounds, to no avail.--There are times when walking around on the world map you are accosted by bandits, raiders, whatever, only to enter combat (if you choose) and find everything dead.  Good for the free loot, bad because you never know what will really happen!--The game crashes from time to time AFTER combat is completed.--Some game choices have to be made on the spot, you do not have a lot of time to fart around and trying to figure the puzzle out.  You take your time, (drowning boy for example,) he will die.  Some people may not like that part.--With no tutorial yet, character creation can be.. difficult.--Finally;  some characters you may spec for conversation bonus dialogues, sale prices, et-cetera.  Once you enter dialogue, there is no way to change who is talking, so in cities, towns, you want to lead the party with the talker if that is your thing.Again, it is a beta.  So far, overall, great.  Most of the cons I have listed will be fixed (I assume / hope) with end product.  If you can look over those things for now, you will not be disappointed.  ESPECIALLY if you like RPG, tactical combat, decision making, and crafting.I do not typically write reviews, but I wanted to get one out there since there are a lot of negative reviews.A hidden jewel for a game, even in beta.  I give my nod of approval."
,Recommended,240760,12286849,"Posted: 29 September, 2014",all,Kozzy-New Curb Your Enthusiasm!,"One of the first rpg's I ever played was Wasteland 1 as a youngster (Either first or second). I have great memories from it, at the time it was something very new and different. Years past by and when I was a bit old Fallout 1 came out, while not the same it was great to play a game with the same ""heart"" as my beloved Wasteland 1. Then came Fallout 2 which was even better and Fallout Tactics which was alot of fun to. Years later Bethesda does a new ""next gen"" fallout game with fallout 3, which while good for the mainstream and new players to the series, to vets it just wasn't the game we had hoped it would be. It didn't have that fallout (or wasteland) feel to it, the story was crap, most the characters extremely dull and overall a game that just realy felt like Oblivion with guns (as annoying as that saying was to me before fallout 3 came out, it did ring true for me after fallout 3 came out and I beat it).Thankfully Obsidian came to save the day and released the wonderful Fallout New Vegas. I was excited by this, Obsidian has alot of old Black Isle devs (guys who made fallout 2) and sure enough the showed Bethesda how to do a proper fallout game with there engine. A bunch of factions helped, Obsidians wonderful writing for the story helped, the dialogue was well done, interesting characters, great voice work (John Goodman? Hell yes), it felt ALOT more like the early fallout games (it just had that fallout feeling, something fallout 3 just couldn't nail)..After all that we have Brian Fargo bringing his talents to Kickstarter and getting Wasteland 2 kickstarted. What we have here is a wonderfully crafted game, jam packed with content, Wonderful writing (characters, story and dialogue), tough choices that matter (best since Alpha Protocol and New Vegas decisions imo), great atmosphere, fun gameplay, Controls are good and a great job of balance (especially in the skills and character builds you can do). For new comers asking ""What is this game like? I never played wasteland or Fallout1/2!"". Well it has a bit of Wasteland 1, a bit of fallout 1/2 and a bit of xcom all mixed together. The turn based combat is a joy to play and doesn't get boring as each battle can be different then the last.You're choices actually matter in this game, you might make a decision and not think about it, only to have it come down on you later as it shows the consequences of you're choice. The game does a wonderful job in the writing department as I said above, having Chris Avellone from Obsidian helped in this aspect and it shows. Characters you meet are interesting, the dialogue is very well done and the story keeps you very interested. The game world is harsh and unforgiving, you better make you're decisions wisely, always make sure you have ammo and medical gear and be on you're toes. You will thank me later :)This game is deep, complex and I friggin love it. The game has come a veyr long way since it was in alpha, at first the UI they had was terrible and I was worried this was really going to take away from my enjoment of the game. Thankfully though the developers tried some new versions, listened to fans and in the end made the UI a ton better. Alot of missions have multiple ways of doing them, you will find yourself either playing the game 2-3 times or saving the game and seeing how different decisions or actions effect the game and the world around you later on. Sometimes I find I have made the right decision at first and then hours later you might hear of bad things that happend because of what you picked.The game is not perfect, there is a few bugs, I wish there was more visual customization for characters and the graphics are not the best, but the good far outweighs the bad in this  new modern crpg. If you are looking for a new rpg that has hundreds of hours of gameplay, great replay value, wonderful writing, nice atmosphere and great gameplay give this game a go ASAP. You can really tell that this game was crafted with love, no publisher telling them to get it out early or telling them what to add to make it more popular. This Brian Fargo and his team at there best and this is a testament to old school rpgs and doing kickstarter/early access the right way.After spending 100+ hours on this game (and plants to play atleast another 100-200 ours), I can say it was well worth the wait, it is one of the years best games and that I am very excited to see what InXile comes with next for there new Torment game. If it is as good as Wasteland 2 we are in for another treat and another resurection of a charished old school rpg. 26 years after I first fell in love with Wastelands charm we get Wasteland 2 and Inxile sure did deliver, this game rocks boys and girls. There are a few things I wish where in the game and a few negatives but 95% of this game is a masterpeice I must say. As someone who has been playing rpgs for 25+ years, this is just what I wanted from a Wasteland sequel, good writing, fun gameplay, interesting characters, tough choices and tons of content. In a day and age where old game series get new reboots and games totally different from the original games, it is a breath of fresh air to have a sequel to an old game be JUST what the fans of the original want."
,Not Recommended,240760,12259627,"Posted: 27 September, 2014",all,wozron,"This game isn't so much 'wasteland' as 'wasted opportunity'.Where Fallout/F2/FTactics were self-explanatory in regards to mechanics and tactics, this game mistakes 'complexity' for 'depth'.I play tactical turn-based (TTB) for the pleasure of planning and setting up effective ambushes and assaults and despatching enemies efficiently. It is this element that is at the heart of all turn-based tactical games, from Silent Storm and Jagged Alliance through to the original Fallouts. Wasteland 2 throws this aspect of the genre out altogether. What is not clear is whether this was intentional, or just the result of really incredibly poor game design and a lack of knowledge of what the genre is all about. Remember, Wasteland was an RPG, not a TTB, and Wasteland 2 has not made the transition well. It's not RPG enough to be an RPG and not TTB enough to satisfy the TTB grognards.The combat system is borked. There is no tactical complexity to the combat at all. In all real combat, the side with the initiative tends to win. In this game, initiative automatically goes to the enemy. No setting up mutually supporting arcs of fire then luring the baddies in. No, you set up your mutually supporting arcs of fire, fire a single shot, then the baddies swarm you.  You only get to try to gun them down when they're next to you. They are able to run across the map to get you.My 'leader' toon has an assault rifle. When he fires a single shot to initiate combat, enemies (even those outside his range of fire) have the opportunity to run fifty or sixty yards and initiate hand to hand combat before he can fire a second shot. It's ludicrous to include a semi-automatic rifle in the game that fires the equivalent of once every fifteen seconds. A hundred years ago, soldiers with bolt-action rifles were firing aimed shots every two seconds. Does InXile understand how firearms work?The probability engine is also borked. It's not uncommon to miss 5-6 60% shots in a row. This also extends to other skills such as lockpicking or safecracking. Many other people giving negative reviews have also commented on this.The presence of indestructible objects (ie, the vines in the Ag Centre) that block progress until other goals are achieved is inexcusable, especially considering the confusing and unclear mission objective system. You literally cannot approach a mission in any way other than that deemed appropriate by the developer.The character development process is bizarre. Your Strength stat has nothing to do with your strength-related skills. Your Charisma stat has nothing to do with your social interaction skills. You may as well put all your points into Intelligence to maximise stat points on level up and enough into Agility to maximise your action points in combat. To reiterate: no matter how rubbish your stats are, as long as your skills are high enough, most of the stats really don't matter.I completed Fallouts 1 and 2, and got as far as I could in Tactics until the bugs killed the game, and never felt as frustrated as I have with this game. The fact that I have 20 hours invested without even completing a single module says a lot about the game.The graphics are, to my mind, no better than we saw in Fallout nearly twenty years ago.  But I could forgive that if the core gameplay was there, but it's just not. The tactical aspects are ruined by an idiotic system that ALWAYS gives the enemy the initiative. The mission log system is unclear and confusing. There are booby traps on at least a third of the items, doors and chests EVEN IF THERE IS NO REASON FOR IT.I applaud the attempt to bring Fallout-style gameplay into the present day, but this game is just a wasted opportunity. I wanted to believe, and instead I just wasted $40.What a tragic waste of time and money.EDIT:You know what?The only thing funnier than how bad this game is, is the number of people who keep comparing it favourably to Fallout 1/2/Tac (bearing in mind those games are 10-15 yers old).The only thing more tragic than a wheelbarrow full of cute puppies on fire is the number of fanboys who cruise the negative feedback section giving 'not helpfuls' to people trying to steer unsuspecting buyers away from this piece of crap.It's just sad."
76561198000466913,Recommended,240760,34418200,Posted: 22 August,all,Tandberg_J,"August 22nd 2017: W2 Review by Tandberg_J (steam account name)(tandbergj@gmail.com)Summary:“The absolute dream for fans of the classic style of Fallout 1, and Fallout 2, and it's still a good game even if you are just casually familiar with Bethesda's Fallout reboots.”This review is for the Director's Cut Edition, which in 2017, has been mostly debugged, and is very stable. I play on a PC for the record, and can't comment on the console ports. But, I've played and beat the original PC version as well, before the director's cut was released, so I've seen the game's development and refinement. (I recommend learning how to edit your save game files, [they are plain text .xml files,] as this allows you to avoid some glitches that might affect your game in purely mundane minor ways, and you can avoid little annoying bugs like not getting credit for a small side quest) Also, you can edit your characters and give them some clothing and aesthetics that are not available in the vanilla game. But this is optional of course. Also there is a huge mod scene for this game, which I can't really say I've tried.Use the wasteland 2 Wiki and online strategy guides often, as they will lead you in the right direction. It's not cheating or spoiling, use the guides as needed, as this game is so much a sandbox, that the guides are more like suggestions for strategies than they are “How to beat the game.” This is NOT a linear game. Of course, it has an ending, and two world maps, but how you get through them is completely up to you. And of course, every local will factor into the final ending depending on what you do with the people there. And also of course, there are ways to fail and end the game early, NOT including just getting killed in combat.Now, here goes the formal review:I am a hardcore fallout 1 and 2 (refereed to as F1&F2 hereafter) fan from back in 1998, which was the year I purchased F2. Then, later that year, my friend and I bought him F1, so we played both religiously as teenagers that summer. We beat them both, but kept playing because of the replay experience. Honestly, the Bethesda Fallout Games, with ""Fallout:New Vegas"" being my favorite of the three, NEVER lived up to the quality and fun of the original Fallout Games, which as most know, were developed by Brian Fargo and the crew at Black Isle Studios, and published by the behemoth Interplay.(FO3, FO:NV & FO4) are the only AAA Bethesda reboots of the Fallout Series of Games, that exist at the time of this writing, and I know there are many people who share my opinion about the original F1&F2 being superior to Bethesda's rebooted games. This review is written for this crowd, which is the crowd that is old school and shares the love of classic 2D Fallout. Still, if you are more of a modern Bethesda Fallout fan, I invite you to play Wasteland 2, and experience some of the old school good stuff that inspired Bethesda to buy the damn franchise, trust me, you will like it!At the very worst, you will be challenged and pushed harder, and put out of your comfort zone, in a nuked out hell, in what's left of The Earth. That is not to say that I didn't purchase and enjoy all three Bethesda Fallout Games. They just weren't a true “Fallout Game” to me.I never played Wasteland in the '80s, and I only knew of the game when I played F2, because I had read online that ""Fallout"" was the spiritual sequel to Wasteland. I've played all the “Fallouts.” I played Fallout Tactics, which was kind of disappointing. The only “Fallout” game that I haven't played is “Fallout: Brotherhood of Steel” which was a game that was released for the PlayStation 2 console in 2004.So, having played all but one of the AAA all Fallout games, and completing them multiple times, with different characters, I can say that ""Wasteland 2"" is an Old School Fallout Fan's ultimate dream game. Because Wasteland 2 (Hereafter refereed to as W2) was able to be crowdfunded and released with no big name corporate publisher, it is basically everything a fan would want without the generous helping of ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t we see so much in the Bethesda Fallout games. Gone is the patronizing, annoying use of nostalgic imagery for the sake of keeping the franchise ""looking like"" Fallout, while changing the game mechanics. Gone is the whitewashed, predictable story lines that don't touch on more mature and morally complex themes, because Bethesda wants maximum profits, because they need to market to teen demographics. Gone are the silly 3d first person graphics, that don't add to the story line, and are too realistic, but fake enough to raise an eyebrow, and just pollute the immersion. Gone are sputtering frame rates that jar your experience. W2 may have old school graphics, but they are just like the ones in Fallout 1&2. They are old school, minimalist, gritty, and damn post apocalyptic looking. Just like Fallout, Even the GUI in the game is made to look like a bad 1980s computer system. This makes it very immersive.A key difference between the Wasteland Universe, and Fallout Universe, is this: Instead of the 1950s retro futurist setting of Fallout, Wasteland has a 1980s retro futurist look. So in W2 you don't have all of the 1950s influenced music and style and imagery. In W2 all the 1950s stuff is replaced with 1980s style cyberpunk music, cars, dialogue, clothing, etc.. This is the key difference between the franchises, and I find that other than this difference, the two game universes share too many similarities to even name.As merely one example of many game play systems that W2 has reverted back to in “the old school way,” W2 returns to our old favorite system of having two weapons, pictured in a gray box at the bottom middle of the UI, and the player, being able to switch back and forth without a cost to action points, can use the two weapons. Also, W2 returns to purely turn based combat system, which, to fans like us, is refreshing. Like the good old days, you get to meticulously plan out each round fired, decide when each enemy is shot in the legs and crippled, and decide when each packet of drugs, or mystery medicine, gets IV'd into your veins. While Bethesda's Fallout's “V.A.T.S.” system was a nice try to bring this turn based combat back, I didn't feel it was a proper replacement for turn based combat. And in a game like W2 or Fallout, I prefer turn based combat. If you don't feel this way, perhaps W2 isn't your game. But that said, maybe you would like W2 as it will pull you out of your FP shooter comfort zone. I think the veteran fans will all agree, that combat in classic Fallout and Wasteland games is best when it is TURN BASED ONLY.In wasteland 2, you create not one, but 4 player characters that you get to control like they are your own character. (Think “Baldur's Gate” here people) No one of the 4 characters is more important or in control. So it's different from Fallout, in the sense that you get to role play 4 unique people, that you create abilities, character portraits, and backstories for. And out of the 15 or so NPCs  you'll meet in the game that can join your party, up to three of them can join your party, making your party size swell up to seven playable characters. This doesn't include characters that are merely following your party, even animals and mutants will follow you at times. I've seen up to 11 creatures and characters on my screen following my 7 PCs. Even goats and cows have been in tow. I once had 6 cows following me around, so chew on that!Also, welcome back to the game that plays from a top down view. Technically W2 is a type of isometric view, yet with a slightly oblique projection (Like Fallout 1&2), which allows some walls to be seen better from certain angles. We will just call it isometric, for simplicity's sake. But that's not what is the most important thing about W2. The view is just like F1&2 which is a huge plus.What is important about the view though, is that W2 is rendered in po"
,Recommended,240760,12146920,"Posted: 19 September, 2014",all,Crazy Al,"I've preordered this game, via steam, as an early backer. I can only speak for the beta, which I would give 8.5/10.This game is a tactical RPG (Think Final Fantasy Tactics, Fallout, Might & Magic) with a setting in a post-nuclear wasteland (Think Fallout, but different). The REAL spiritual ""Fallout 3"", the story is a successor to Wasteland 1, but NOT a requirement to play the game, it's completely standalone.The biggest strength of this game is: The feels. Early on (15 mins) you get a choice which will immediately change the storyline in a minor way.Over and over you will feel the sting of the game as your actions bite back in an emotional way.Ask yourself these two questions, and then you're ready to play this game:""Do the needs of the many really outweigh the needs of the few?"" and ""If I save this man from death, how will I know he will not harm others?""Game on, brothers and sisters."
76561198098173191,Not Recommended,240760,28176735,"Posted: 3 December, 2016",all,falconfused,"This game is so close to being awesome. The characters are fun, the world is immersive. The weapons upgrade system is alright. Exploring is fun.The combat is what is really difficult to handle. The grid system is horrible. During regular movement, characters can move and stand in what seems independent of a grid system. But when combat starts the characters are forced into a very clunky grid formation. This makes diagonal shots somewhat of a cheat when hiding behind ""cover"".  Also, there is no way to move your party in a formation, which means that when walking into an obvious ambush, there's no way to keep your party in good order. They just move into a lump.It's hard to have a good time with the combat system with these limitations."
76561198029126609,Recommended,240760,18632763,"Posted: 22 October, 2015",all,Padishah,"I first played Wasteland 2 back when it was finished. Its was a damn good game but with a couple of issues here and there but overall a really fun game that was essentially the closest thing to Fallout 2 since Fallout 2. (I love the original Fallouts almost as much as I love the new ones.)Im happy to say the Director's Cut version is a massive improvement over the original. With a multitude of fixes and additional content/mechanics to make the game feel fresh. Its overall the superior experience. It does still have a few bugs, a few confusing quests and overall slow pace early on in the game but despite this the game is great fun.For those of you that dont know Wasteland 2 is the sequel to the original game from the 80's and a spiritual  sequel to Fallout 2. Its an isometric turn based post apocolyptic RPG, one of the few of its kind. You have some really in depth character customization/rpg elements and some really damn good combat. Seriosuly its great, its even better than X-COM's combat. Overall if you love Fallout, RPG's, post apocolyptic games and have some patience then Wasteland 2 Director's Cut is the game for you!(Note I have deleted my original review and updated it with this one)"
76561198009173518,Recommended,240760,25372565,"Posted: 5 September, 2016",all,Something completely different,"Wastelands 2. What to say. First off, if you like turn based games wich offer immersion, depth and an enjoyable long story then this game is for you. Wastelands has quite some really good things going for it but some flaws as well as I see it. I'll try to list them below.Good:- The setting. Really well done. Heck, the intro made me misty eyed and I felt my emotions responding to things happening in the game more then once. I was quite touched when a companion died for one and really came to loathe the bad guys even if they weren't bad for the sake of being bad. All the factions made sense to me and their struggles were a delight.- Your choices and actions matter. Maybe you don't see it at once but very often you do see the results of choices later in the game, sometimes quite subtle. Well done! Actions have consequences. Quests almost always have more then one way to solve it.- The combat system is well done even if it isn't entirely balanced and I feel some stats (speed) and weapons (assault/ sniper/ late game heavy) are better then others (luck/ charisma and melee, shotguns and hand weapons.)- The game looks quite nice. The locations are quite varied and ussually carefully made. Some minor locations and battle scenes were slapped together or recycled though. It takes a while to fully explore a town and that's good.- Lots of easter eggs and hidden secrets - you are rewarded for taking a good look as opposed to rushing through.- The voice acting is really well done, adding to the immersion.Not so good:- Quests tend to need a string of actions to be done in exactly the same the correct order to get the optimal solution. Who cares if I order first and then put coins on the counter or vice versa in the shop? This is a source of frusteration. You also likely will look untill you are eighty or crack and shoot everyone for the solution of some quests without using the internet. Ye gods. This would have ruined the game for me more then once if the story wasn't so compelling.- The difficulty spike half way the game is beyond silly. For a few encounters you have to fight vastly superiour enemies with hugely sub par weapons. I don't enjoy duelling a fully armored knight with a wooden sword thank you. After you find some new weapons the difficulty goes back to a much more acceptable level. This really needs a fix.- I didn't like the first major choice and how it would doom people no matter what I did.If you can live with three two above points I think you should grab the game, pin on your desert ranger star and start patrolling Arizona."
