76561198109158166,Recommended,240760,23907549,"Posted: 28 June, 2016",all,DankSerpico,"You can't actually write a review for the Directors Cut because... Steam. I have 94 hours logged on that game and finished it so, here's my review then!In many ways a throwback to classic isometric PC RPGs. Can be brutally difficult at times but I enjoyed the challenge. There is some degree of learning curve to deal with as well. Basically if there is a stat you can level up, it's probably useful. Do not sleep on Kiss♥♥♥♥♥ Smart♥♥♥♥♥ Hard♥♥♥♥♥ and Perception. Even Toaster repair is pretty useful. Other than that, explosives are your best friend. Unless the explosive in question is one of the many land mines you will step on... hence why perception is important.I wouldn't say it's an incredibly ambitious game but it gets the job done. The game seems to run fast and largely bug free. The graphics get reused a lot and really aren't anything amazing. You'll see the same character portrait several dozen times. They actually seemed to have crowdsourced a lot of the assets. So you funded the game... and you kind of made it too... It may be spartan, but it may finally push you to get off your♥♥♥♥♥and make your own game in Unity.When it comes to cons, the worst part of the game would have to be the VO. I played the majority of the game without headphones on. Some of the voice actors sound very amateurish and seem to want to drag out their lines for an eternity. I can only guess this was a backer reward or maybe one of the developers owed someone a favor. Other than that, the music is decent enough.In some ways Wasteland 2 was more enjoyable than Fallout 4. There are many times your decisions actually have impact on the outcome of the story (F you Preston Garvey!). The sense of humor, while juvenile, gives the game a nice vibe that contrasts with the dark subject matter. It has much more personality and challenge than Fallout 4 but it is also more ballsy and ""adult"" in subject matter.If you love classic isometric RPGs then give Wasteland 2 a shot."
76561198169358900,Not Recommended,240760,29578657,Posted: 29 January,all,jhatou,"Old-school to a fault. Buggy as all hell, even in its Director's Cut form - and this is basically what stopped me from finishing it. The way the game is designed makes you think that you can really solve many quests in oh so many different ways, but your creativity is unlikely to be rewarded, as approaching a task from an angle not intended by the developers may run you into bugs\unfinishable quests. It is also very long, and with the problems mentioned above, plus the turn-based combat making things even slower (and I do normally enjoy turn-based combat), it becomes a drawn-out slog. Waste of time, only for fans of the genre so hardcore as to not care for the (utterly unpleasant) pain that this game brings alongside its intended experience."
76561198032369915,Not Recommended,240760,26435930,"Posted: 5 November, 2016",all,vukodlak,"I really wanted to like Wasteland 2, but in the end I feel it failed me on most counts, the first and foremost being the writing, to the point where I couldn't muster the will to finish the last mission after 81 hours in (Director's Cut).The good?* Squad management with all the skills and weapon types is actually fun.* Combat is enjoyable enough.* The setting has some gloriously bizarre moments and characters.But all of it is undermined by shoddy execution, overall simplistic writing, lazy and uninspired artwork (honestly, Fallout Tactics looks better and put more effort into customizing character portraits) - all the things that kill immersion and suck the fun out of the game.As far as execution goes, there're plenty things in the game that feel unfinished or unpolished. Pieces of dangling quests here and there or failure to react to you doing things in wrong order, small things like rearranging squad formation or viewing completed quests sorted in order, reused locations - all contribute to the death of a thousand cuts. Squad management fun is obliterated by the fact that your companions don't level if you leave them at the base, which effectively means that you'll be stuck with almost the same party throughout the game. So much for recruit diversity.But what really killed the game for me was the writing. I'm honestly struggling to see the lauded brilliance here. It's a pulpy shlock, by design, sometimes funny and eccentric, but so over the top that it kills all tension and willingness to care. It doesn't know what tone it wants to set. On one hand it attempts to be grim and portray a ruthless wasteland, but most such moments go hand in hand with cartoonish grotesque hilarity. First third-to-a-half of the game is a tedious linear slog. The Prison -> Canyon -> Damonta stretch is a dreary and dull timesink with no redeeming qualities or payoff. But when it suddenly becomes somewhat more open, you are still offered only cartoon characters, clear cut black and white choices and moustache twirling villains. The choices are obvious, the outcomes are formulaic, quest chains predictable, no subtlety, no suspense, no stakes. The one moment of doing something different literally happens during the 2nd assignment, and that's that, the only trick up Wasteland's sleeve.It probably sounds a bit too harsh and bitter. If I had an option, I would've given WL2 a mixed review. Ultimately it's a game that can be fun but is undone by its flaws, and in the end looking back all I feel is frustration and disappointment, so I can't honestly recommend it. ...The first Shadowrun Returns also left a sour taste of disappointment in my mouth. But it was followed by Dragonfall and Hong Kong - two games I love to death. Here's hoping that inXile could only go up from WL2."
