,Recommended,240760,34260722,Posted: 15 August,all,GarrickWinter,"Note that this is a review of the Director's Cut, which I completed in about 40 hours but doesn't seem to show here.While the visuals may feel off-putting at first and the outright excessive amounts of skills and junk loot can get overwhelming, Wasteland 2 ends up being a pretty fun and compelling post-apocalyptic RPG.There are a diverse set of places to visit and people to meet/help/kill, and a wide array of weapons and challenges that you can respond to more or less how you like. I enjoyed dealing with the story quests and occasionally breaking into places to bypass problems, and there were a few pretty neat characters among the bland ones. The ending sequence was quite well-done, with a few genuinely surprising moments capping off story points from throughout the game. Combat feels suitably weighty and sometimes chaotic, and there are plenty of weird tidbits scattered throughout the wastes.Overall a good and enjoyable game, though it does have some typical CRPG flaws - voice acting was inconsistent, there was way too much loot to manage, and narrative quality was inconsistent too - some of the characters or scenarios lacked imagination and relied too much on tired tropes, even though others were fun and interesting."
,Recommended,240760,23697743,"Posted: 21 June, 2016",all,Casket The Clown,"Wasteland 2 is a post-apocalyptic CRPG created by InXile Entertainment. The long overdue sequel to the 1988 game Wasteland, it takes place in the western United States, in Arizona and later California, after that brutal 1998 nuclear war that totally happened. You create a squad of characters, all new recruits to the ""Desert Rangers,"" a group trying to bring a semblance of lawfulness back into a desolate wasteland.Wasteland 2 can be seen as the spiritual successor to Fallout, as it's viewpoint, combat, and general feel is much closer to that than the original Wasteland. The combat is somewhat similar to the original Fallouts, although much more focused on in this game. Instead of controlling a single character with companions being completely AI, the game allows you to control each character on their turn. This adds more of a turn-based strategy feel in the combat; it's more about positioning and tactics than straight up firepower and ability to withstand said firepower. Fallout Tactics holds a similar, albeit clunkier, playstyle. The different skills are pretty good for the most part, although some weapon types do stand out as more useful.The freedom in this game seems scant at first, as you are immediately forced into the Desert Rangers and sent off on a mission, but diverges almost right away with multiple choices as to where to go first, who to help, etc. Only one time limit is imposed, and this time limit simply alters the game rather than ending it outright like in the first Fallout. Folks who prefer the darker side of life also have the option to go rogue in one of two ways, but I'll leave those up for you to discover. It's not completely open world, but more a sequence of maps linked by an overworld map.The graphics get the job done, but they're by no means stunning. Running in the Unity engine, the optimization is okay. The general aesthetic is certainly good, but it doesn't quite jump out at me like Fallout 1 and 2, or even Wasteland 1. The primary complaint would be the character models, they're not too distracting, but they aren't exactly the fluffiest sheep in the barn. To say it bluntly, the character models are bad, and at times don't even match the portrait of the character in question.ProsCombat system is complex and strategic, especially compared to it's predecessors.Freedom to approach situations, although combat is less avoidable.The world itself is goodVarietyConsCharacter models aren't very good.Some skills aren't as useful as others, although most are fun to use.Can be difficult for a first-time player.Final Thoughts:Fans of its forebears will find it pretty enjoyable, and certainly a worthy successor, and anyone who needs that CRPG itch scratched will be plenty happy with it. Those who like fast, action-packed games will have to look elsewhere.Rating:9/10This review was written for and is published on theLit Reviews [LR] curator page."
76561198047102011,Not Recommended,240760,12534949,"Posted: 17 October, 2014",all,Arngrim,"Ultimately, Wasteland 2 is an average game that scratches a particular nostalgia itch for many gamers and is receiving praise beyond its merits.  Quite frankly, the Turn-based strategy genre has been in a drought for nearly a decade and fans are dying of thirst to the extent they'll lap up contaminated water riddled with disease and ask for seconds.  They're so enamored with a sub-standard product they don't recognize they're dying a most dishonorable death from dysentery.Combat - The combat is lackluster and is not tactical nor strategic in any sense of the fashion.  OK Corral gun duels might be more appropriate, except slow and with none of the skill involved.  If you want a game with good combat, just replay XCOM2012 or Xenonauts.Character building - No skill tree, no perks, nothing to be found except redundant skills to simply dump your stat points into every time you level up.  If you're looking for the complexity and fun of a D&D style character sheet, keep looking.  If you're looking for a Fallout perk system... keep looking.  Even Diablo 3, which the avid fans of W2 seem keen to mock, has a far more indepth character building system.Story -  Glaring plot hole at the beginning of the game that most people seem to overlook or simply not notice.  Even if you look past that, the only clever aspect of the entire game is the little Easter Eggs you'll occasionally find.  However, finding kitty litter, a condom, or big black didlo for the 15th time is just sad.  It's funny the first time, but like any good joke, you have to know when to quit effing telling it.  If you want a game with a good story, reboot Mass Effect, BG, Fallout... pretty much any other CRPG.Characters - Easily forgettable and none that will be remembered.  No Minsc & Boo, HK-47, Commander Shepards, Irenicus (best villain ever), Tomi Grin Undergallows etc.  No Delita or Ramza to be found here.  For the most part, they're as bland and lifeless as the Arizona wastes you'll wander around for the first half of the game.Exploration - Some of the environments are interesting, but with the terrible combat and random loot, much of the fun is taken out of it.Graphics - The game wasn't trying to inspire us with graphical prowess or eye porn, but what it delivered is unpolished and ugly.  Some will argue it's stylistic or gritty, but to each their own.Sound - Ok, but no gripping musical scores to be found here.At the end of the day, everything W2 set out to do has been done before (obviously), but done far better."
