76561198030775494,Recommended,240760,13806482,"Posted: 3 January, 2015",all,Arkatreides,"Not disappointed!First of all, Fallout 1 and 2 (FO1/2) were some of my all-time favourite games when I was younger. I never played Wasteland 1 and only heard of this when I started playing Fallout, by which time it was already 'dated' and I never bothered to play it (which might have been a mistake!). I was quite disappointed by Fallout 3 (though New Vegas redeemed the franchise for me). Yes, it was graphically more advanced but it totally lacked the feel and freedom that FO1/2 had. Sure there was a ton of stuff to do and the world was rich, but where it lacked was the way you customized your character and your inventory. One of the things that made FO1/2 great was the sheer amount of weapons (most with multiple ammo types/modes) and it always felt that stuff was scarce and you had to use the right tool for the job.So when Wasteland 2 was announced I was apprehensive: Would it stand up to FO1/2? I am pleased to say that I am not disappointed, and in some areas it even surpasses it.Here are a list of things I love about this game:- The party system. It has been a while since we had a great game where you can control all members of your party (another great game recently being Divinity Original Sin). Even FO1/2 only had a main character plus one companion model. The fact that I don't have to discard 90% of items because my main cannot use them is very refreshing. I also don't feel like I am missing out on stuff because among all members of the team someone will be able to cover it.- Meaningful skills. Every skill (well maybe almost every) is useful throughout the game and needs to be constantly leveled. However it's not hard to build a party that covers everything. And this again goes back to the party system. You need to create a team that complements each other and not just dump everything into guns. In fact one member in my party only had a rudimentary fighting abillity but turned out to be the most crucial to success throughout.- Tons of items. Lots of weapons, all customizable. At the same time ammo is scarce, especially at the start. Rely on melee to save bullets (this is reminiscent of one of the first fights in FO1 when I had a pistol with 3 bullets...).- Tactical combat. The combat is fun, positioning matters and many a fight can be won by changing tactics or preparing better by positioning the team. Combat doesn't always start at line of sight which gives you the opportunity to get everyone in a favourable position.- Meaningful decisions. I wont spoil too much but the decisions are there and meaningful and not just a simple try A, reload, try B. Sometimes it's only hours later that you realize what effect your actions had.- Humour. There are some great easter eggs in there that add to the humour. It's not as overboard as FO2 was but it has the same wacky ideas.Some areas where the game shines less:- The graphics are somewhat outdated. Personally I don't see this as too much of a problem (they are nowhere near bad) but if this concerns you, it might be a problem.- There is a LOT of text. Don't expect everything in voiceover. Very little is covered. Again, not a problem as the dialog is well written and worth reading, but nothing for people with short attention spans.Overall I would thoroughly recommend this to anyone who loved FO1/2 or any classic RPG.9/10"
