,Recommended,240760,20686613,"Posted: 22 January, 2016",all,[EHJ]ironslasher,"This is a classic, a truly enjoyable game. It returns to the old school fallout scheme centered on impactful decision making freedom and character development centered on alternative ways to approach objectives. It is openworld in the way that the old fallout games felt openworld, but not so much in the way the new ones do. It is more linear in the sense that it is event driven, the locations tend to tie into the main story in some way, and the main questline ends the game.Notes - mostly the cons you should be aware of:1. They've created great characters, but they still don't feel ""alive."" There is no day/night cycle, characters simply sit in their placed spots on the map and you interact with them via admittedly well done dialogue options. This is helpful at times, like when you want to find someone. That said, the lack of movement and life in the characters themselves could've been handled better. Games like Arcanum managed to do this to perfection years ago.2. The wasteland environment doesn't feel dull (a problem I had with F3 and beyond); the environments feel varied, pretty much all the groups and locations feel unique.3. Not a great deal of weapon/item variation - You just slowly progress up the pricepoint chain as the game goes on. Would've liked sidequests or encounters that wouldve opened up more unique options in this regard. Also, other than for reasons of bullet scarcity, the game doesn't give you a compelling reason to ever use smgs, pistols, or even melee characters to a certain extent. There is no need to mod weapons to get through the game, and weapon mods are also pretty standard.4. Main story is solid, but the side quests are really where the game shines. The decision-making freedoms are absolutely excellent and consequences change the game in real ways. Lots of text, but not problematically so."
76561198027254884,Recommended,240760,15287628,"Posted: 9 April, 2015",all,aragorn,"Summary – 7/10 Good game for those who like post apocalypse setting, top down 3rd person point of view, large variety of weapons.  Buy when on sale for under $20.Pro:+ Post Apocalypse setting+ Lots of decision trees, dialog options+ Multiple ways to complete an objective+ Interesting story (bringing law and order to a place of total anarchy)+ Decent number of quests (about 60-70)+ Nice unique maps+ Dismemberment, melting on some kill shots+ Easy to use UI+ Humor and funny references especially of the 80’s throughout.Con:- Lacks the immersiveness of 1st person viewpoint games  (Fallout: New Vegas, Fallout 3)- Can’t interact with most of the environment.  Almost all building entrances are blocked and using explosives won’t change that.- Poor AI – just set up an ambush point on a map send out a meat shield to draw the enemies and kill them as they approach.  Works almost every time.- Explosives so overpowered in combat.  They never miss even if your character doesn’t have a single point in explosives. Give meatshield a ton of STR (which equals HP).  Have enemy mob him.  He runs out then toss grenades.  Battle won. Rinse. Repeat.- Game maps are fairly linear (except for Titan Canyon)- Dull weapon/shooting animations (just one animation for all weapons)- Non realistic skill (Toaster Repair (really!!))- Poor stat optimization.  Intelligence > all.  Many stats just not important.- Too many skills focused on just opening containers (open lock, tumbler, alarm, trap, perception) since you have to divide up skills amongst players to max them all quickly it means switching through multiple players just to open a container.  Pretty poor design.- Every container is either trapped or has an alarm attached to it (or both).- Few locations (Less than a two dozen maps in the AZ and CA zones)- RNG on skills is not even close to what is listed.  50% chance of success really means 10% chance of success at most.  Use PF9 and PF11 constantly can waste 10 minutes opening a chest/safe not very enjoyable.- Easily broken quests. Lots of reloading to complete a quest.- No mods or modding community (lack of replayability)Note my playtime means nothing as I have a small child now and often have a game running/paused on one monitor all weekend even though I may only play 15 minutes every couple hours when I have a few minutes to relax.  Probably only spent 25-30 hrs actually completing the game.In general if you are a huge fan of Post Apocalypse games like me then you will enjoy this game.Not too many bugs in the game just a few like:- Examining ground that says something is buried but not allowing you to use a shovel or any other skill on the ground.  This happened 3-4 times.- Trying to save after visiting a travelling merchant to offload junk.  Get a message saying “you are in combat and can’t save at this time”  Guess the merchants don’t like the deal they received hehe.- Memory Leak (At least when you pause the game for 2+ hours and then unpause the game it moves slower than molasses. It’s a pain if you forgot to PF9 before hitting pause. (Use a liquid cooled Alienware rig as my main gaming machine and it’s a beast so they lag/stutter and huge decrease in frame-rate is due to a memory leak).Though please note that it is not even comparable to Fallout: New Vegas with its fully interactive environment, open world, 1st person view, great soundtrack, number of factions and locations but for a budget/on sale game this is something to enjoy for awhile.  Still not sure why all the most valuable items (skill books) in a post apocalypse world would be stored inside toasters.  Also be sure to PF9 before using any skill then PF11 when it fails will allow you to open every intractable item in the game.  Also press “Z” a lot to find all intractable items."
