,Recommended,240760,13872963,"Posted: 6 January, 2015",all,AZ19999,"This is really fun game, when i play this, it just reminds me a of a crossover between Mount and Blade and Shadowrun.The game ""travel"" system is like mount and blade where you take your group on a journey through the wastelands of arizona trying to do all the nobel stuff that rangers do. The problem is that you have to avoid radiation and check your water levels so you dont die of thirst or radiation poisoning. while that may seem easy it can be pretty annoying to have the shortest route blocked by radiation and to take a detour means that you have to waste all your water and you end up with a dehydrated and tired group walking into an encounter. The encounters on the map are about as annoying as pokemon, imagine walking through a big grass field for an entire game of pokemon, imagine how many encounters that would be. EXACTLY! Besides those issues the world map is very well done and contains many other things to find like travelling merchants, treasure and watnot.The encounters are completely random, but most of the time you'll just be fighting either, bandits, animals, etc... but for the others it can be things like merchants, towns etc... so you get the point of encounters.The character leveling up system is interesting, at the start of the game you can either pick from a list of default characters or customise and create your own. it gives a pretty balanced set of skill and ability points to start you8r character on a certain playstyle. At the start of the game it will provide ytour characters with starting weapons based on their skills. To level up simply get enough XP and then use your radio(explain later) to call command, they will says soemthing like  ""CONGRATZ YOU GET A PROMOTION"" then you get the appropriate ability points to use one your character(s).The Radio is a unique part of the game, you use to pick-up sidequests, recieve calls/updates from command, and get issued field promotions. you will just get random transmissions, important dialoge and other watnot from the radio, also the frequency changes by itself so you dont need to worry about that.Combat is much like certain classic games, your characters initiative skill determines what order your turn is in, and works as a top down turn-based rpg. all of your actions require Action Points so it's important to conserve them, any excess points will be carried over to the next mission.not gonna talk about the storie because spoilers mate GO PLAY IT YOURSELF!so yeah...9/10 would kill a raider again"
76561198032583913,Recommended,240760,23645131,"Posted: 18 June, 2016",all,fpgrgurich,It crashed my imac 3xtimes.  I had to hold the Shut Down on back of computer.
76561198046704321,Recommended,240760,11690609,"Posted: 13 August, 2014",all,Blackfly,"Finally broke 100 hours with this gem.  This game is EXACTLY what was promised, and delivers where it counts.  Fans of the original game and the post-apocalyptic genre should eat this right up.  There's at LEAST 25 hours of content in the Arizona portion of the game.  With that being the halfway point we're looking at a 50+ hour game which is more than most games today will give you for the pricetag.  There were no corners cut or shortcuts taken and it's very evident in the late beta.  The game is highly polished and the bugs are (almost) gone!  The expectations are very high for release (Sept 19th?) and I fully believe InXile won't disappoint.Synopsis:  You are a freshly recruited Desert Ranger in the post-nuclear wastes of Arizona, USA.  Welcomed and rushed straight off to investigate a prominent ranger's death and complete his critical mission, the game wastes no time showing you the harsh and dangerous environment that is the Wasteland.  Through use of skills, combat, dialogue, and cunning, you will forge a unique path through the wasteland and write your own story as a member of the Desert Rangers.  Of course there's mutated plants and animals, killer robots, raiders, cannibals, thugs, and radiation clouds to keep you company along the way.The Game:  Unlike most games that ease you in with kiddy missions and tutorials, this game slaps you in the face.  ADAPT OR DIE is the theme for the first few run-ins with the bad men and creatures of the wastes.  If you're unlucky enough not to recruit a special friend before setting out, you'll be lucky to survive to the first real location without a ridiculous number of reloads.  On my first playthrough I was losing team members in the first 10 minutes.  Then I realized the coolest thing about this game:  You have to actually THINK.  About Everything.  The combat is highly tactical, and the choices have real consequences.  There's actually no way to do everything in one playthrough.  With each location you visit you'll make decisions that affect the rest of your game.  And the consequences don't show up until later, making your choices semi-permanent (you REALLY don't want to reload and replay the last 1.5 HOURS to fix that dialogue choice).  This is one of the most immersive top down TBC RPG games I've ever played.  It is very much a spiritual ancestor of the Fallout series, but the playability is very much with the times.  You can also have a party of up to 7 members, which is much more than other games have allowed, but furthermore in my playthrough of just the Arizona area, I encountered 6 recruitable NPCs and I know for a fact I missed at least 1 due to a choice I made.  So there's probably upwards of 12-15 characters you can add to your party throughout the game, which is a  TON!  And there's so many ways to do everything!  Locked door?  Pick it, bust it down, or find the key.  Broken robot? Fix it mechanically or hack the cpu.  There's a real sense of reality applying in this world.  If it makes sense, you can probably do it.  I must commend the developers for that specifically, as it's frankly an amazing thing to see in a game.  Also, in many situations you can avoid combat alltogether, or you can choose a side and manipulate the outcome, so there's just as much variation to the game strategy as there is to the skill use.  It feels very complete in the way of forging your own path.Combat:  The combat in this game is a bit more complicated than your typical tactical turn based game.  Aside from the usual Action Points system for movement/weapon use, you also have to deal with weapon jams, your NPCs going rogue and doing whatever they want for their turn, and rampant friendly fire if you don't watch your angles.  The only way to avoid this (and you can't ever avoid it entirely) is to invest survival points into your weapons and leadership skills to minimize the chance of jams/rogue turns.  Some may find this a frustrating addition to combat, but I find it adds a great depth and believability to it.  To compare the combat to something, I'd say it's similar to XCOM but with more of a Fallout RPG focus, so it's not nearly as hard once you get the hang of it.Overall this game is what Post-Apocalyptic gamers have been waiting for since Fallout 2.  If you enjoy turn based games and love the genre, it's bound to become one of your favorite titles for any number of reasons.  The story is huge, the choices are real, the combat is deadly.  Do you have what it takes to be a Desert Ranger?"
76561198035707258,Recommended,240760,23510756,"Posted: 11 June, 2016",all,TrafaglarLaw,"The rpg element of this game is reminiscent of how a tabletop rpg functions. I have played this game and became easily engrossed. The post-apocalyptic setting comes across pretty well too.There is certainly plenty of action and tactics to be had in this game, however, the puzzles it presents are sometimes tedious to figure out. Whether it is because you don't have your camera rotated the right way to see the interactive elements, or because you have to travel through three map sections just to get the piece to solve the puzzle (and then travel back) there does seem to be a bit of tedious work at times.The instruction-as-you-go tutorial works fine. It isn't too obtrusive if you don't want to look at the tips. However, it is a basic tutorial and some of the things you have to figure out yourself. Such as the green and red bar above weapons indicates optimal range values.I wish there was multiplayer for this game but unfortunately there isn't. I think it would be a lot of fun  for a group of friends to each control a character, but whatever."
