76561197982243937,Not Recommended,240760,12224267,"Posted: 24 September, 2014",all,__,"No mindexplosion hereWasteland 1 was a revolution. Games on the C64 were simple. Some of those guys and girls created The Bard's Tale and The Bard's Tale 3. They were my childhood heros and a big influence. Bard's Tale series were also quite simple but also quite addicting. Simple 21x21 dungeons with riddles and traps.Then Wasteland 1. Characters had skills. A major step forward. Instead of ""You see enemies at 30"" would you like to (F)ight (A)dvance or (R)un"" you actually saw the enemies. People from your group could break out of formation and move towards the enemy while the rest remained stationary.But what really was special about Wasteland 1 was that there were areas you couldn't enter at the beginning and all you had were mechanical and brawling weapons. And you slowly progressed, solving riddles, making your way. There was one town that didn't allow you to enter and after many hours you finally got ahold of some energy weapons. Yeah baby! And you returned and blasted those arrogant ♥♥♥♥ guards' heads off, looting their armor and weapons and ammo. Then you progressed inside the town to try and solve the riddle, the mystery. Mind blown, truly.Now Wasteland 2.First of all. It's a generic, linear and tier based game with a main storyline and sidequests, all nicely placed in your journal. The first quest after the starting zone quest might seems like it gives you choice but that's just an illusion. It doesn't matter which one you pick. You'll have to go through certain main storyline areas regardless. A game on wheels.There is no skill tree. The tree is a list. And you have stuff like Toaster repair. One would imagine that after a nuclear war toaster repair would be the least needed ""skill"". Something like camp building, scavanging, weapon repair or armor repair or digging or climing sounds more like it would be something that would be needed after a nuclear holocaust. There's nothing like this. It reeks of simplification and consolitis. A game for the WoW generation.The graphics.... boxes. Everywhere. Characters look like they're straight from Everquest 1. Basic low-poly models. It's ugly. Buildings are boxes. There is no art. It's just boxes. Zones are designed like ""hey let's place this box here and that box there"" ""and place a safe here and another container there"". Everything looks the same. Bunch of boxes.The humor... well some might find it funny that some guys dressed in black and nuns carry ♥♥♥♥♥♥ around. Anything remotely philosophical doesn't exist in this game. It's like watching explosions on TV all day. Just that there are no explosions. The story is flat and uninteresting. The humor is like ""look someone said♥♥♥♥♥♥♥teeheeheee"" aimed at 12 year olds.Progression, as said, is linear and tier-based. Every weapon has an upgrade. This one does 5-12 damage, next one does 8-16 damage. The ""weaponsmith"" skill lets you disassemble weapons for mods or junk parts. Both can be sold, mods can be applied. Since your inventory is always more or less full you have to pick the weaponsmith skill so your're able to make some money to buy ammo. The majority of the game you'll be managing your inventory, trying to open containers and running around. Zones are made intentionally that you have to spend quite a while running around so you have the impression of huge zones. Worst example is the railway station map. If this game has 60 hours of play time 30 are spent on walking around.Wasteland 1 was an innovator. Wasteland 2 brings nothing new on the table. We've seen this before in other games and better. It promised that my mind would explode like a blood sausage. No it didn't. Nothing mind-blowing to see here apart from the bland, uninspired game. And only because the games of the last 10 years were mostly ♥♥♥♥♥♥ console ports doesn't excuse the game to be released in this state.Voice-overs? Few. Most dialogues aren't voiced. Only ""important"" NPC ones and only the first 1 or 2 paragraphs. This game is unfinished. There are game-stopping bugs. For instance you're asked to leave a party member of yours as a hostage until you solve a quest. You solve the quest and when the part member is about to return to your party instead you get a message that your party is full. You can't hire new members since the size of your party magically shrunk to 7 instead of 8. But you still have to carry around all its gear and ridiculously heavy quest items you can't dispose of because they're quest items. So inventory management got even more annoying.Man this game sucks. And if you voice your opinion on their forums you get banned for it.They blew at least 3 mil USD on this and some say they earned over 6 million. The game is a Wasteland sequel only in name. It's a bad game. Maybe in 2 years if they're not too busy working on titles they're really interested in like this deaders game what's it called again.. Torment you might see a game that's worth the money spent, not invested because you don't invest in Kickstarter games you give them money up front so they can create a game they would like to make and you won't see any profits but a bare-bones game like this.A bare-bones game. No fluff. Don't waste your money on Wasteland 2. It's not worth it."
