76561198002863073,Not Recommended,240760,12292018,"Posted: 29 September, 2014",all,bortengineer,"Don't get me wrong, Wasteland 2 is not a bad game. The problem is that it's not a good game either. At the beginning It definitely gives you that sweet feeling of an old style RPG, but as you go deeper into the game, you start to realise that it's just the surface and Wasteland 2 is pretty dull at the inside. It's not about some major issues, the problem is that there are huge number of small ones.1) Game mechanics is not transparent. Do you know that high combat initiative allows you have more than one move in a turn? Do you know how luck affects drop rates? How charisma works, is it party-based or character-based? Do you know that formula for action points is (STR+INT+SPD)/4+CRD/2. Sure, you can dig forums and find answers to most of your questions, but you can't find them in game.2) Boring levels. Maps are quite big and full of hidden crates and containers. There are no shortage of mobs as well. It makes progression tedious and dull.3) Most skills are poorly designed. Computer science, demolitions, lockpicking, safecracking, toaster repair - in 95% of the situations you use them to get access to some loot. And you really need that loot and those skills, because ammo is sparse. I found that Mechanical Repair and Animal Whisperer to be enjoyable, just because they are not used routinely.4) There are dosens of crates, safes, and blah-blah on the map. Almost all of them contains some junk, a little bit of ammo and tiny amount of money. It makes the gameplay grindy and tedious. Instead it would be much better to remove 90% of the crates and fill remaining 10% with cool items, and give the player feeling of the accomplishment.5) The storyline is not engaging and full of cliches. It really fits theme of original Wasteland, but what was good back in 80s is boring and repetitive now. It reminds me of Fallout Tactics, which is not cool. To be fair, there are good things about the story as well: i really like emphasis on hard decisions and ""you can't save em all"" attitude.6) There are times when game really breaks the immersion.  First time you see a honey badger - it's really funny. Second time, it's ok. But when you see a whole valley full of them, you just facepalm. There are no day/night cycle (fallout 1/2, arcanum, hell - even Ultima 7 had that). And yeah - dosens of crates full of staff in what was supposed to be a wasteland.7) And list goes on and on.Note, that none of these issues are gamebreaking or something. They just take away some satisfaction of the game. So if your are a fun of post-apocalypse theme and turn based combat - by all means get it, but wait for the sale. Otherwise - avoid."
76561198026534943,Not Recommended,240760,12530932,"Posted: 17 October, 2014",all,Farside,"First off, I like this game.  If you liked the orginial Baluders Gate or Fallout you will like this game.  Feels very much the same except for my reason to NOT RECOMMEND the game.  BUGS BUGS BUGS.  Not the fun kind you can shoot, but the bad kind the made about half of my quest lines to not finish (I played Hollywood after Patch #2, and it was still hand many many broken quests).It was not just that the quest would not clear from my logbook, but also that quest in the actuall game would lock up and be unfinishable.  I'm sure if I did it in the right order, it may work, but in a game like this, it is very easy to not do things in the ""correct"" order (you kill the guy/steel the intel/destory the base/etc.  before getting the quest).  The game was clearly intended to be finished and explored in any order the player feels is correct, but the scripting does not support it.Other little problems:1)  NPC Pictures did not match the text descriptions or the model about 90% of the time.2)  Lots of unclear timers.  Timers are ok, if the player really understands what they should be doing, otherwise not fun.3)  Old school interfaceMaybe after a fan made ""fixed"" verson of the game's scripting is done, I would recommend it (or patch number 10 or so comes out)."
76561198046946973,Not Recommended,240760,12533433,"Posted: 17 October, 2014",all,v312ym34n,"3/5I've been playing Wasteland 2 and feeling a little disappointed. It's too retro.The pacing is on the slow side, and it's not the best-looking game.OK, it's set in a post-apocalyptic wasteland, but character designs and backgrounds can still look good. Like, the environments of Bethesda's Fallout 3 were dramatic and beautiful even if they were all drab gray ruins. My performance should not be this poor for a game that looks like this.And the skill use is just a touch too slow. If one needs to save-load-spam to get past a lock, or if there are a lot of mines to disarm, it's tedious.And the combat does not feel as dynamic and tactical as, say, the X-Com remake's. There's really only 2 options: headshot and burst, otherwise one crouches the team and shoots and that's it for tactics. X-Com's system encouraged much more movement and flanking, as well as having special abilities by class that affect tactics. And of course, Divinity: Original Sin introduces a lot of tricks with spell interactions that can control the battlefield, or that rapidly move characters around the battlefield. Compared to X-Com and D:OS, the combat in W2 feels primitive.Also, it REALLY needs formation options. It's damn tedious having to individually click on the characters to spread them out before triggering combat. Most of the time I just have them clustered up non-optimally because I can get away with it, but it would have been nice if there were Baldur's Gate style formations. If there is an option for this and I'm just too slack to find it in the interface, please, tell me.If I hadn't played Divinity: Original Sin or X-Com, I would probably really enjoy Wasteland 2. It's still a decent game, but it feels like D:OS just does it better. It's prettier, the combat is more fun, the pacing is better....Wasteland 2 feels like there was a little too much old-school thinking limiting their design decisions.And some of the mechanics just plain feel WEIRD. Like how disconnected attributes are from skill use. Or the way energy weapons work with armor. There should NEVER be a situation where it's better to have lower armor, that's just dumb.Plus there are too many skills that cover similar things like lockpick + safecracaking, 3 skills all covering dialogue, etc. Do shotguns, rifles, sniper rifles, smgs really all need separate skills? It ought to just be small arms, long arms, energy weapons and heavy. It seems COMPLETELY random that toaster repair requires its own skill.Normally, I'd still recommend this game as it's still above average, but there are SO many great games out or soon to be out; I would hold this purchase until it's on sale.I'm frankly astonished at how many people seem to love it. I mean, it's okay, and I'm still going to finish it, but they write like they love it. Did they not also play Divinity: Original Sin, an also crowdfunded game that is superior in nearly every way? I loved the old school rpgs too (the Fallout games, the Infinity Engine games, the gold box games), but a great deal of the good feelings around this game seem to be driven by nostalgia more than what it actually delivers."
76561197961689516,Not Recommended,240760,12264471,"Posted: 27 September, 2014",all,PHJF,"Hints of greatness marred by poor design.If one's goal as a developer is to revive classical game mechanics, one has to be sure of actually improving upon them.  Wasteland 2 is ultimately a pale imitation.  The Unity engine powering WL2  performs poorly, looks bad, and is accompanied by fairly unimpressive audio throughout.  The crux of the game, combat, is unbalanced and uninteresting.  But for all its faults, is Wasteland 2 worth a play for true fans of the long-dormant genre?A big part of making a believable wasteland lies in making sure the details standout.  With few exceptions, WL2 fails to create the visual and audio cues necessary toward really immersing the player.  Instead of supplementing the audio/visual presentation of an area, WL2 instead opts to incessantly hurl descriptive text.  What would have been a charming callback to games of yesteryear is instead used, endlessly, in an attempt to cover up lackluster design.  Environments and the denizens therein are hopelessly underdeveloped, with the biggest culprit being the severe lack of character portraits.  I've met no fewer than three distinct characters all using the exact same portrait.  In a game prided for its community support, surely the developers could have reached out to fans for some more variation.  Character models themselves are messy, blurry, blocky affairs complemented by unnatural animation.  But enough about presentation; true fans of Wasteland, Fallout et al would never disparage a game for not looking like it was developed by Crytek.They would, however, disparage a game for playing poorly.  Right off the bat, player creation hammers the player with boundless stats whose longterm value is questionable at best.  How does .1 combat speed affect units?  How about +1 initiative?  What's the difference between selecting 4 intelligence and 5?  It is all too easy to hamstring oneself out the gate because the game does a remarkably poor job explaining all this.  The value of character skills runs the gamut, as well: after selecting a Mechanic skill for one of my units, I progressed through the game  almost never having been able to use it.  Why is lockpicking separate from safe cracking?  Why is alarm disarming separate from trap disarming?  Why can virtually any character, regardless of skill, use the supremely powerful (and rare) explosive weapons to perfect effect?  The skills screen tells me ammo for assault rifles and sniper rifles is more expensive than for handguns and submachine guns, and yet later on in the wastes the opposite holds true.  When the absolute basic mechanics at work in a game are flawed, the entire experience suffers for it.Speaking of flawed mechanics, how about that combat?  In a word, it's broken.  There's a slew of weapon types from which to choose, but some end up being significantly stronger than others.  Player characters never have quite enough skill points to be godlike killing machines, and if you've chosen poorly, there's no way to get those points back.  For a great stretch of the game my party featured two melee characters, but the few weapons available to them put said characters at an enormous disadvantage.  The heavy armor you'd expect to pair with such combatants instead hampers their movement to such a degree that they may spend half the battle simpliy shuttling between enemies.  And the enemies?  In a game featuring up to seven player-controlled characters (Take that, X-Com!), competent AI is a must.  Unfortunately, and this is the absolute biggest thorn in WL2's side, the AI is consistently absent.  The tactical combat WL2 aims to deliver flies straight out the window from the outset.  When combat begins, rather than units flanking, sniping, crippling, and controlling one another to sweat-inducing effect over the course of several nail-biting turns filled with careful planning and deliberate execution (ala the recent X-Com game), it devolves into one amorphous blob of units colliding with another amorphous blob of units until one blob lies dead.  Mainstays of tactical combat such as cover systems, range limitations, flanking, unit position, fields of fire, suppression, crippling wounds, stealth, targeted shots, etcetera etcetera are either completely absent or barely qualify as being in infancy.  Without fail, combat begins with enemy units covering several screens worth of distance on the first turn to stand directly in front of my characters.  How such tragically broken combat (in a game filled to the brim with it) made it to release is beyond me.So, the bottom line: is Wasteland 2 worth playing?  This is a tough.  On the one hand, as a gamer who grew up on Fallout, Jagged Alliance, Silent Storm and, yes, the original Wasteland, the prospect of an old-school video game renaissance thrills me.  The relative success in crowdfunding of Wasteland 2 and similar games proves I'm not alone in wantingmoreof its ilk.  Anything is better than nothing... right?  On the other hand, as somebody who puts Fallout 1 and 2 (and yes, even Tactics) up on a pedestal, looking past Wasteland 2's myriad faults becomes too difficult.  On its own, it may be an acceptable diversion.  But next to developer Brian Fargo's previous masterpieces, it simply doesn't hold a candle.  Significant patching and/or modding could remedy or obscure some of the more fundamental issues, but in its released state, I can't recommend Wasteland 2."
76561197993221160,Not Recommended,240760,12268643,"Posted: 27 September, 2014",all,HexiDave,"First few sections of the game felt pretty solid, but the second half of the game in particular really seemed to drag on. Worse, bugs started cropping up more and more often. NPCs getting caught on objects mid-movement in combat causing the game to become stuck permanently, cutscenes playing off-screen, broken quests, typos in the dialog, redundant quest items wasting inventory space (mostly the rad suits - how many times is the same plot point going to be a major quest line?), fairly weak voice-acting (Matthias in particular), and just a slew of ""little things.""There was never really any point where the game grabbed me, which was probably its biggest failing for me. There wasn't any story or dialog that blew me away, and the combat never grew into anything special. It just felt like they took what they did in the first game and made the safest possible sequel they could. I constantly had a feeling the developers saw what they had and said, ""Eh, close enough"" and called it a day. I can't even remember a point where any of the voice actors really raised their voice beyond speaking volume.I'm sure patches will clear up a lot of the technical issues and typos, but the underlying problems are probably going to last."
