,Recommended,240760,11526487,"Posted: 2 August, 2014",all,Ajaxis,"Now only a few days from release, I can easily say that this game is well worth the high price. Brian Fargo's latest work is a crater-deep, atmospheric tabletop-style game, bringing back the best aspects of Fallout and the original Wasteland while leaving behind the clunky interface. This is what a turn-based RPG should be, what Fallout 3 should have been. This nonlinear game somehow manages to have better storytelling and immersion than games that actually try to pull the player along any kind of linear path. You know how a lot of people advertize their experience as being full of choice and freedom? Here is the game that actually means it. No tutorial, no big opening scene, you get about a minute of instructional dialogue for your first mission and then you can go wherever the hell you like, and the game spontaneously punish you for trying to explore so early, like others might.Genius turn-based combat system, inventive characters, perfect DnD Campaign fuel, oddly colorful post-apocalyptic world, and a haunting soundtrack to back it all up. I'm definitely gushing, yes, but this is the one experience in an RPG I've had that has been the closest to absolutely flawless."
