76561198039108757,Recommended,240760,14861632,"Posted: 13 March, 2015",all,Captin,"I never played WL1 unfortunately, it seems, I had missed out on some good old times. While it was provided with WL2 I can't find myself playing it, I have no history with it so I'd probably just find it frustrating to play (given its age). Anyways...I dove straight into WL2 having no background of its story aside from it was the idea behind Fallout, or so I've been told. It's exactly what you think it is, a strategy game based in a wasteland. If you loved the play style and strategy of X-COM then you're going to love this one.Creating your own squad of rejects is a fantastic feature that really give this game a personal touch. That piled atop the countless types of skill sets and passive ability makes the combinations limitless. You start out in a group of scrubs as a sort of Robin Hood squad beating up on those that choose absolute power over all.The game is combat oriented, obviously, but contains plenty of story elements and dialog to make a well rounded adventure. The combat is a pause-based system, meaning that out of combat you remain in real-time however once you enter combat you're dropped into turn-based. Fights play out depending on your team composition, skills, and most importantly the type of opponent you're facing.Non-combat related sections are filled with witty dialog and at times strange challenges that require certain skills to surpass.My pain points are primarily in the chance-of-X percentages, which seem entirely incorrect, many of which are probably quite easy to fix if they choose to do so.-Critical failures: This causes so much rage it's unreal. Seemingly a 1% chance here feels like 99.9%. WHY...it's a joke.-Rogue chance: This is most definitely broken, proven when a squad mate with a reduced-to-zero chance went rogue on the FIRST TURN. Even after every turn he went rogue...-Broken cover seems to be a big problem, obvious walls which should be providing the bonus...don't.Side notes: I would highly recommend the save/char editor merely as a respec tool. Why this wasn't included as a training feature in the game baffles me. The skills can be confusing for most people and incorrectly allocating points can be a real game breaker."
