,Recommended,240760,14215383,"Posted: 28 January, 2015",all,namgrim,"Oh wow... I finished Wasteland 2 and it took me over 70 hours. At any point it didn't feel a waste of time.How have I been missing the genre. I'm talking about old-school CRPGs with turn-based combat and that really feel almost like P&PRPG:s. The gamer really plays a role. For me, 90's was the golden age of gaming, spawning CRPGs like Baldur's Gate series, Planescape: Torment and the first two Fallouts.I was worried if Wasteland 2 would be too hard for me. In the nineties I used to play a lot PC games, but as I've gotten older, I don't invest so much time for the gaming anymore. Also, today's video games are more easier and I though I'd be spoiled. But I was wrong! Yes, Wasteland 2 is challenging, also pretty frustrating at time to time, but it is also so compelling that I want to play it more and try harder. The difficulty is spot on.The game is fugly. I mean the game world graphics. It looks like something from the early 2000's when the 3D graphics were still awkward as hell. On the character portraits and all the drawn 2D stuff are decent and cool. I personally don't care much about the graphics, though. The audio is good. I especially love the ambient (Fallout-ish) soundtrack by Mark Morgan. It really sets the mood for exploring the vast desert wasteland and the ruins of the past world. Also the voice acting is well executed.Combat is a major part of the game. People have complained that it is not tactical enough. I don't know about that, I don't care. When I bought Wasteland 2, I was buying an RPG not a tactical strategy game. So, I like the turn-based combat as it is. Well, addition to the headshot, more targeted shots would've been nice, but you can't always get everything.I liked the main and side quests. There seemed to be several ways to deal with everything and the player's choices really have effects in the Wasteland. The story and dialogue was well written. There is a lot of text to read, but I don't mind that. You like reading a lot of text or you don't — its' really just a matter of taste. I do understand gamers that just want to ”play the game, not read a book”, but I enjoyed reading the dialogue and all kinds of item descriptions and little jokes here and there. The game is immersive as hell and it just sucked me inside its world.Wasteland 2 is not perfect, but it truly is a great game. I hadn't enjoyed playing a new videogame this much for many, many years."
