76561198063144733,Recommended,240760,15442460,"Posted: 18 April, 2015",all,gnometorule,"A wonderful, deep, pretty, funny, and extremely long game - I clock 252 hours at the time I'm writing this, and this is my first playthrough which is quite a bit from finished (I restarted maybe a few hours in, and must have kept the game on a few times while not playing, but I doubt this accounts for even 50 hours). You can certainly finish faster, but if you try to obsessively find and do everything (and which true RPG fan doesn't?), I doubt by much if you read all dialogue and such.I'm an RPG, and more generally fantasy old-timer. I've played D&D all night through each Saturday back in the mid 80s, and later the Baldur's Gate series, etc. Strangely, while I owned it, I never finished or even progressed much into Fallout, but from the first steps into this game, this felt like the real deal from 20 years back with a very attractive new chassis.While the game allows for much optional questing and is largely open-world, it also guides you along nicely, so you rarely have to wonder what you could do next, which I appreciate. The character animations are awesome, with special shoutouts to enemies in wheel chairs, or those whose legs you chopped off sometimes still crawling for a few seconds before collapsing. :) Voice acting is excellent, and plentyful; and by the end of the game, you had enough background text to read that it amounts to almost a short book. The UI is great and allows for easy access to really everything, with little gimmicks such as the game allowing for automatic intelligent loot sharing (but, in line with RPGamers being OCD, who would want that? :)). The skill system truly matters, and you'll miss out on a lot if you don't cover ALL skills among your team (which you can, by and large - I skipped two somewhat useless skills only).And so much of the dialogue really cracks me up...my favorite is probably the leader of the robotic faction who keeps advertising on air with demented marketing such as to not follow another leader who'll just enslave you, while he'll kill you prganic vermin as free men! Another recent favorite was the third prize in a lottery organized by a gang leader which was described along the lines of ""you'll get to work on my farm...which used to be your farm.""I'm playing on normal. On this difficulty, the game is somewhat easy after the first few levels. I personally like that as for the first playthough, I focus on story; and as there are two higher difficulty levels, I assume those looking for a challenge can find it too.Looking for something to criticize, I find:(1) Occasional in-fight freezing - not the game, but the camera, which means typically that you can no longer use your team and need to re-load. It's very rare though. I've noticed a few other small bugs as well; none even close to game-breaking(2) Occasional un-finished scripting (e.g., if in a Cali town you act like the usual good guy and kill the ""Leather Jerks"" (Tom of Finland type men all wearing fashionable chastity belts), a lot of the dialogue and such that follows doesn't quite fit what really happened(3) Weapons are very unbalanced. That is NO negative for me (it's single-player, so who cares?), but might be for some(4) Attribute 'intelligence' is WAY too important. You'll be a fool to not have an entire team of brainiacs, all with maximum intelligence of 10(5) The team doesn't grow too much on you, as you have no inter-character dialogueBut this is really a game that I expect anyone who likes classic RPGs will not like, but adore (if you're a WoW PvPer, sorry, you're not an RPG fan. I'm talking about those being in it more than anything for story, setting, and atmosphere).Get it if you haven't yet!"
