,Recommended,240760,12757693,"Posted: 2 November, 2014",all,Zealot,"What an amazing journey it's been, exploring the world of Wasteland 2. I bought into early access for the game due to how promising it looked during the kickstarter fundraising, and I was not disappointed when the game delivered on nearly every point it set out to do. You throw in a bit of imagination throughout the game, and you're immersed in a world that feels incredibly reactive to the player, and completely welcoming of choice.The characters I made were each custom tailored to their respective roles, given custom portraits, backstories, and eventually came to have little moments which had me growing rather attached to them. Firefights took a twist when I pictured battles in more gruesome detail than was shown ingame, and really helped make my characters that much more exciting to play with. The combat mechanics are fairly well polished and offer a satisfying turn based combat system with different aspects which you can use to influence how a battle goes, and there's a multitude of systems that are incorporated into it. The world design was well enough that I knew what was going on, but also simple enough that through reading the flavour text descriptions of everything around me - it came alive.Everything I did in the game seemed like it had alternatives that would be just as if not more successful than my choices, and world navigation whether through conversation or skill usage was so damn versatile I was consistently impressed. Break a lock when trying to pick it? It's a good thing you've got a mechanic on your team to fix that for a second attempt. Break it again? Try brute force on your bruiser and see if they can smash it open. Fail a third time? Looks like those sticks of dynamite you were carting around will come in handy all of a sudden - let's hope the loot is worth a valuable commodity! Have you been speaking with an NPC and find a particular speech check has come up? It's a good thing you've got a party member who just so happens to have a way to influence them in a special way. Are you lacking in that aspect, or not proficient enough in the one you need? You've got plenty of other ways to go about finding your way through the world, it just might take a bit of searching. A good deal of challenge was offered at varying intervals throughout the game, and it felt quite fair on normal difficulty - save for a couple fights which really ramped up the difficulty suddenly. A well rounded team and proper use of what is at your disposal will allow for you to pull through however, and you'll feel good in the end.Sound design felt like it had some nice character to it, and the soundtrack to the game ended up being stuck in my head for days when I wasn't playing, making me wish I was back with my Rangers and roaming the wastes. Graphically, well, this was probably where the game lacks the most in its current state - and likely to be a good candidate for improvement. While I appreciate the fact things were kept a bit more on the simplistic side so that my imagination could take over, there were times where certain areas looked a little cheap and hokey, effectively breaking immersion. More options for character customization would always be a plus too.All in all, I spent over 70 hours for a single playthrough of this game, and I enjoyed every second of it. Coming from somebody who's about as jaded as they come with modern video games, this is an impressive feat and I give my praise to the team for doing such an amazing job. This has to be one of the best cRPG titles I've played in a long time, and one which I've been highly recommending to friends. Can't wait to see what's in store for us next, whether with updates or DLC for this game, or a third game some time down the road!"
,Recommended,240760,12766376,"Posted: 3 November, 2014",all,Dr. Kobra,"It'll make you feel... like a Fallout virgin, irradiated for the very first time.It's not perfect, and it can get frustrating at times, but it's got all the right vibes - and a ridiculously overwhelming amount of content."
76561198036728376,Recommended,240760,12832345,"Posted: 7 November, 2014",all,Cloud,"Great reboot. Wasteland 2 came with the original, so if you don't know the difference and how well WL2 pays homage to the first, then you're in luck.They are still currently patching and updating the game at a regular pace. This updating is nice, it shows the Devs are still working on making the game as epic as they can."
76561197997301797,Recommended,240760,12786064,"Posted: 4 November, 2014",all,Weaponer,"This is the closest thing to Fallout 1 and 2 you can get today. On the pro side it has that perfect signature blend of dry Fallout-grade humor, atmospheric locations and a healthy pinch of postapocalyptic madness. Some NPCs and factions are just awesome (MAD monks surely the best), your own team sometimes makes epic remarks about locations you are on, and the thousands of small details scattered around make it a living, breathing world. Another hallmark feature of Fallout, its famed non-linearity, is implemented in nearly every single quest here, though as a Ranger you don't get a chance to become a really bad guy. Your actions really matter, and your inaction matters too, sometimes. And if you read lots of bad press concerning its flawed, bug-ridden state during the release, fear no more: there are a few minor bugs left for sure, but none of them will ruin your play, the developers did a great job of patching the game.But there's a contra side. Combat sucks. It sucks like hell. In 2014 one would expect at least some degree of tactical thinking on the side of AI enemies. Come on, guys, Jagged Alliance - even the first one! - did a better job of maneuvering twenty years ago. And even a scripted ambush is better than no ambush. Mowing down rushing mobs gets old as soon as you develop some reasonable firepower and deal with initial ammo shortages, i.e. on your second day.And there's the balance problem at last. At some point in the game you simply stop getting better firepower and armor because there are no bigger enemies to kill. I realize that this issue was caused by the need to let everyone finish the story, but there are many reasonable ways to solve this particular problem, starting with adaptable level of enemies. Instead the game chooses to punish meticulous players - basically its core audience - with arrested development and infinite boredom during its last chapters.In the end I believe this game deserves to be played and enjoyed once. Just once, though. These days you don't get anything better anyway."
76561198013477836,Recommended,240760,12750096,"Posted: 2 November, 2014",all,Nix,"If you loved the classic Fallout 1 and 2, you'll thoroughly enjoy this game. The post-apocalyptic setting was masterfully executed - not too recently ruined, just enough that civilisation is attempting to rise from the ravages of a bygone age. The characters you meet are colourfull and interesting enough to entertain but still maintain that seriousness that forged survivors need to continue living.Combat is satisfying, its simple and straightforward. It does encourages specialisation, but with a party of 4-6 rangers, you can cover for each character's weaknesses. There's also the custom character option which is nicely implimented, with option to choose from a set of pre-made kooky characters to wander the wastes. The skill system is gratifying - you'll get that wide grin when you realise that one skill that you first thought off as useless, (Toaster Repair... Seriously?!?!) suddenly has relevance when you encounter it.Only downside to such a good game is the length. Its a solid 10 hours if you like to explore and immerse yourself on the story, possibly less than double that amount if you explore all the nools and cranies of the game. But ultimately, it leaves you wanting more - In a good way mind you. Wild West post-apocalyptic Rangers never sounded so cool, untill now."
76561198032221650,Recommended,240760,12793519,"Posted: 4 November, 2014",all,amfalleur,"This game is a flawed masterpiece.  The first two-thirds of the game are excellent, ranking up there with the original Baldur's Gate and the Icewind Dale games.  For me the threads started to unravel quickly during the last third of the game.  Numerous quests such as stopping an underground slave trade are introduced and then dropped without a clear resolution.    Playing the game through twice, I still can't tell if these latter quests are broken or if I simply screwed them up; there is no clear feedback from the game's denizens, which is different from the first half of the game where everyone is saying ""Yea!  You're my hero!"" or ""F$%k you!  Our lives are ruined now!""  If you've played Vampire: the Masquerade - Bloodlines or Neverwinter Nights 2 or Knights of the Old Republic II, you've seen these kinds of problems before.  Content seems to be cut in order to meet a release date, and the overall quality of the game suffers for it.On the plus side, the combat is excellent and the skill system is the best one I've seen since Deus Ex.  I think this skill system should become a standard for any game developer that wants to balance combat with stealth and diplomacy.  The game is also not short; I would estimate it takes 40 to 50 hours to play through every significant section.In conclusion, this is not as good as Dragon Age: Origins or Baldur's Gate II, still the gold standard by any measure, but it measures up pretty well to some of Obsidian's early games such as Knights of the Old Republic II and Neverwinter Nights II.  Flawed but fun."
