76561198052108016,Recommended,240760,12854955,"Posted: 8 November, 2014",all,kurikinton,"I found this to be well worth playing, but it left me somewhat unsatisfied in the end and wishing there had been far more content. After finishing one playthrough, I immediately started a new one but quickly realized that the game would not grab my interest enough for a second one any time soon, though it is partially my fault perhaps.As you can see from my ""hours on record"", I finished the game in under 27 hours (subtracting the aborted second playthrough), so I'm not quite sure where they got the 80 hours of gameplay idea from. As noted below, I take shortcuts when playing, but I wouldn't expect those to shave 50 hours off of play time, more like a quarter at most.As a casual gamer, I very much enjoyed the tactical combat aspect. I actually prefer a ""heroic"" gameplay approach in which my squad usually has the tactical upper hand, as opposed to more hard core players who prefer to have to struggle hard to reach objectives (I just don't have time for that - thus part of the reason play time was shorter, but not all the reason IMHO). As such, I tend to tweak player stats early on to give them a bit of an advantage (just a bit!). I actually found that this makes combat far more exciting for me at least. I would very much prefer a game in which one good shot will lay you, or the enemy, flat, as it would in real life, and tweaking stats can create such a situation (unfortunately for the player squad only). I find the concept of spamming heals on party members to survive an encounter to be *extremely* unrealistic and immersion breaking in anything but a fantasy setting, so the tweaked stats allowed be immersive roleplaying of a heroic squad versus more average opponents. I loved the increasingly effective gear replacements and the gun modification mechanics, as well as the various differences in the tactics required for the weapons, which also helped immersion greatly. Someone else here said that gun ranges seemed the same, but for me, the chance to hit was eliminated as a factor through tweaking, so I could see clearly that ranges were in fact quite important. This suggests to me that some tweaking of balance might actually make this game better for some people. Just for comparison, there are plenty of other RPGs I've played in the past, with tweaks/mods/God abilities etc., where long term playability was in no way effected by that. A truly good game should accomodate all sorts of play styles. Anyway, overall, I found the tactical aspect to be the most satisfying part of the game. Being able to preposition my squad and then draw the enemy into a shooting gallery was actually quite fun. Granted, that also points out the weak enemy AI others have mentioned. The AI does more typically rush into their weapon range and then end up unable to fire because they've run out of action points, making them sitting ducks out in the open. However, in situations where they are already in range and under cover, they will remain there, and they did seem to seek cover if it was close by.I generally do not like scripted games at all. I prefer open world/sandbox almost exclusively, but I make an exception for this genre due to nostalgia from the original Fallout series. Others below have complained about the overall story and how it seems to be window dressing on the tactical combat experience. This was generally fine for me, and I was glad that it was perfectly possible to play encounters in a different order then the ""standard story line"" in many cases (but not all). At the least, doing things out of order did not seem to break anything for me (such as being unable to finish important objectives - with one noteable exception below).On the downside, though, I found that navigation was slow and at times extremely confusing (and thus quickly boring). I found myself repeatedly referring to walkthroughs and the like to figure out what the criptic instructions of NPCs was meant to tell me. It was also very common for important instructions to quickly scroll by to be missed, so I was not even sure what I was supposed to be doing. The worst was a large map midgame where it is possible to get very, very confused and commit immersion breaking mistakes, requiring a reload to an earlier save.The other immensely annoying aspect of the game was the constant lock picking, alarm deactivating, trap removal. Those activities actually took up a huge chunk of each map to the point that, considering that the contents of chests were often literally junk, I ended up skipping over only to miss the occasional important item. Thus, this became an extremely tedious negative experience which greatly subtracted from the overall fun. Also, the question of whether a given container was trapped/locked/alarm protected did not seem to follow any kind of logic.Also, let's face it, this genre and the game mechanics that go with it are really becomming outdated, and this game, while providing a somewhat modernized and, IMHO, polished execution of it, still does not make up for the fact that the mechanics are artificially held back to a kind of simulation of 1990s technology. This to me is the greatest cause for the lack of depth in character development and other such aspects pointed out by others. While 3D rendered, this *is* really a glorified isometric game in presentation, and I found the low resolution of the characters to be a bit confusing in that it is not as if someone is going to be playing this on an Android phone (or is it?) I think they could have upped the resolution of the characters by a bit, and for instance have more of them appear to reflect what they were wearing.Edit: While I'm on the subject of graphics, I have to say that the base model used for player characters is *UGLY*. There is really only one head shape each for male/female, with a few different skins slapped on seemingly slightly off center, and I had a really hard time coming up with characters that came anywhere close to someting I could identify with (this is an RPG after all). This is not a big deal, so I mention this only as a minor complaint.The other thing I found to be *extremely* distracting was that the NPC portrait displayed on screen when conversing with that NPC invariably looked nothing like the 3D character, including clothing, colors, hairstyle, etc. This to me was just sloppy and incomplete. Rather than putting an emphasis on having portraits that would get lots of likes on Devient Art, they should have gone for volume and made sure that every unique NPC had a unique portrait.  Judging by some of the really bad portraits available in the initial character creation screen, my guess is that they hired an expensive artist to do these portraits and ran out of money. That was definitely a design mistake.Certainly the game is visually beautiful to look at (when zoomed out), but after having played the Fallout reboot series and other Bethesda RPGs, which provide a relatively modern immersive 3D first&third person experience in a fully unscripted open world, it becomes increasingly difficult to be fully pulled in by this old-school, scripted, controlled viewport experience.Not only that, but the freedom of the Bethesda approach has allowed very deep modibility which extends the playability of the games for many years, whereas this game ended up being just a minor distraction over a couple of weeks, sort of like a short TV miniseries."
