,Recommended,240760,28161018,"Posted: 3 December, 2016",all,BR BARDO,"After 58 hours playing this game, I wanted to write a review, but I couldn't because I installed the Director's Cut and it would only let me if I installed the original version. I like this game so much that I went ahead and installed the original Wasteland 2 to write about it.Easily one of the best games I've played this year. This coming from a CRPG fan who loves Fallout 1 and Pillars of Eternity. There are few games today with this kind of mechanics and setting, and it is for me one of the best, of course not without its flaws and bugs, but none interfering so much with the experience.Wasteland 2 is a party-based, tactical turn-based CRPG set in a post apocalyptic environment in a devastated Arizona (and later Los Angeles). You have the option to highly customize up to four member of your squad or choose amongst pre-made characters. During the game you recruit several other NPCs to join your team. This game is not text heavy like Pillars of Eternity, it gives you a good deal of text to read, but very manageable. Working with the CLASSIC attribute configuration (Coordination, Luck, Awareness, Strength, Speed, Intelligence and Charisma), you are free to make dozens of different builds, from heavy artillery guy to tech expert to sniper doctor. One nice thing is that you find good use to most of the skills along the game, and most weapons as well are pretty useful (Energy Weapons are very useful later in the game, not so much in the beginning).Choices in this game do not necessarily alter the course of the future, but it's very interesting how you can decide who lives and who dies, who deserves and who doesn't. This makes up for tough decisions and replayability in case you want to make different choices. One tip: Don't do a lot of saving and loading just to see different choices and take the best one; part of the fun is to be able to deal with the consequences of your acts. This is Wasteland, not the Wonderland!THE GREAT- Tactical Turn-Based Combat is very well executed. The ability to split your party, flank the enemy, get behind cover and start some massive shooting is pretty exciting. Grenades and rockets are a MUST for the fun and also to get out of trouble! Many of the encounters are very well made and challenging.- Choices! It'll generally come in the form of you between two gangs, groups or communities fighting each other and you'll have to decide to partner with one, promote peace or kill them all. You don't get that feeling that your choices affect the game in the long run, but the short term is exciting enough, and you can decide key points in the middle of the story.- Tough fights! Getting into a fight with 10 armed guys and/or many robots and getting out alive is pretty satisfying.THE GOOD- The mood and post apocalyptic environment are very immersive- Narrative and dialogues are well made and fun to read, despite some bad acting from some characters.- Music: Some of the music stick into your head (at least in mine) and they set the tone very well.- Random encounters in World Map become monotonous, but they are usually good and not very long.- Quirks and Perks system added to the Director's Cut version may add some juice, especially Perks that you earn each 4 levels; You choose Quirks in the character creation and pretty much forget about them (unless you chose the lightning bolt...)THE BAD- Poor character progression; There is not enough gear to collect during the game. Armor/clothes especially, the different looks you can get is pretty much the same you could've got in the character creation. Some characters may spend quite a while with the same weapon. You do not perceive individual character evolution very well. In the beginning you can use Safecracking skill to try and open a safe with 61% chance; 50 hours in the game you can try and open another safe - looking exactly like that one - with 61% chance and a much improved Safecracking skill. You spend points and in many cases your experience doesn't change.- Player Characters lack personality. See Pillars of Eternity for example, where you have main characters with their own personalities and agenda, plus the ability to hire and customize other characters. In Wasteland 2, You can create your characters, but they don't have personality, only the later recruits do, and it's still just generally some stereotype. Some characters are fun and interesting; many are not, and you won't care about them very much.- Bugs: You'll se them all around, be in the original version or Director's Cut; floating weapons in the hands of your characters, camera that always resets its position once you change area, delayed or mute voice dialogues and so on... none of them ruins the gameplay though.Overall, excellent game for CRPG fans. Played and loved Fallout? Then get this game now!9\10"
,Not Recommended,240760,34103947,Posted: 8 August,all,Javahyls,"**This is a product review for the Director's Cut version, in which I have spent 38 hours at the time of writing. But I can't place a review there.**The atmosphere in this game is amazing, each settlement you visit is a unique location tied to a back story. Characters often have a history themselves, knowing people from other settlements and having an opinion about them. The game itself however, is very bad. It crashes often during loading, looks like it was made in 2008 and it has a large amount of tediousness connected to the gameplay as well as things that are just not very well thought out. I bought the game because I like XCOM and I wanted to have a similar game in a different setting that could run on my Linux computer. But I was wrong, this game was nothing like XCOM and it didn't even work that well on Linux.Pros:* Good atmosphere.* Settlements are unique and exciting.* Plot twists!* Simple graphics (which is a pro for me since it means it ran on my computer just fine).* First run took about 38 hours.* The end is pretty cool, all the friends you made gather to defeat the common enemy.Cons:* Frequent crashes during loading of locations.* Achievements didn't work for me.* One of my characters had the 'Raised in the Circus' quirk and had to run around in a non-removable clown costume the whole game.* There are a lot of useless skills that you only need once during the whole game (or not at all). In addition, you might find followers that have overlapping skills with your core rangers making your first runthrough very inefficient.* Invisible walls of radiation block you from going to certain areas in the overworld.* Characters will gladly shoot through walls for you.* You can't walk through allies. So I had one melee character with high initiative which was often stuck between other rangers. This could have been avoided by allowing allies to move past each other on the same square.* Sometimes you finish a quest before talking to the quest giver, who then promptly gives you the reward. Or the other way around: someone assumes you heard about X before when you didn't even talk about X.* You can't throw away quest items. You can buy multiple rad suits in the beginning (which I did because I thought the bonus stacked), but then you can't dispose of them since they are quest items. Same goes for items for quests that have been finished already.* AFAIK during an ambush you do not spent AP but you can still get the Slayer perk  (no AP spent) triggered, which seems useless to me.* Often the quickest solution to a quest is just to shoot everyone. The quests often involve a lot of walking around clicking on things which make them really tiresome to do.* The enemy can surprise you before you can surprise them in most cases.* In the end you need to have your whole squad specialised in one specific skill in order to be able to defeat the game with ease, which is a shame.* Combat gets repetitive, even with the different types of enemy squads you encounter.* If you free aim a shotgun you have a better chance to hit multiple enemies (or less allies).I bought the game for 10 euro, I wouldn't recommend buying it at any higher price because of the bugs. Most notably the crashes made the game really hard to play. I'll be looking forward to seeing what Wasteland 3 brings, and I hope they will fix the issues in this game."
