76561198104625739,Not Recommended,240760,23500604,"Posted: 11 June, 2016",all,AliceInChains,"I honestly can't figure out the massive positive buzz around this game. Reading some of the 'quotes' from Games reviews sites I can't help but wonder if those reviewers actually played the game, or were simply paid to write something extremely positive completely out of sync with the actual game.Flexibility, depth? Really, where? Having the option between 3 skills and some dynamite to open a safe merely means you have 3 similar skills separated for no obvious reason. And a game mechanic that allows opening a safe by tossing a stick of dynamite at it isn't deep or flexible, it's flawed and oversimplified. C4, plastic explosives, shaped charges, really too much to ask?Perhaps it seems a bit odd that I start off with such an example, but ultimately 90% of the game is just that: utilizing one skill or another. Lock picking, safe cracking and trap disarming outside of combat, and the various weapon skills during combat.One of the biggest gripes I have with the game really. The multitude of pointless and weirdly chosen skills, needlessly segregated (lock picking AND safe cracking, individual weapon classes), with no synergy between them or with the main attributes. The attribute and skill system is so extremely poorly designed that your 10 STR character won't be able to kick open a simple wooden fence (which is even described as being shoddily built), because he lacks the Brute Force skill. That's right, a skill. Dear developers, ever heard the term 'brute force approach'? It's not a skill, it's not something that needs to be learned. Seriously. Well alright, have your 10 STR wield a big freakin' axe and chop down that small wooden fence... No can do, the axe is ineffective against that shoddily built fence. Just like any other weapon, except explosvies.Your 1 STR character with some points in the Brute Force skill however, might be able to kick down the door. Might I say, because the developers also chose to implement some arbitrarily chosen difficulty level to each of such skill checks. The skill rank is still prevelant however, with no connection to attributes. So even if you do decide to give your 10 STR some ranks of Brute Force, yuour 1 STR char with higher rank will still have a better chance to succeed. The ridiculousness of the difficulty settings is perfectly demonstrated in a certain town which you will end up in some time into the game: A large stone wall inside a building can easily be kicked down (as the animation for Brute Force is always the same, just like all other animations for skill usage. Extremely boring, and most of the time character aren't even close enough to actually touch the objects. They're just doing something in thin air), but two shoddily built wooden fence outside are near impossible. As mentioned before you can't destroy them with an axe, or a shotgun either. You also can't jump over it, or climb over it (movements in Wasteland 2 are extremely limited, just like pretty much everything else).So attributes and skills are detached, there's no synergy. The attributes themselves provide very limited benefits, and basically the only things that matter are Action Points (AP) and Combat Initiative (CI). Coordinations would be the equivalent of dexterity in other RPG games I imagine, and maxing this stat to 10 will give you a measly 10% bonus to Chance to Hit. While min 1 gives you 1%. So no penalties for extremely low stats. Developers decided to separate each weapon 'class' into a different skill, Assault rifles, Sniper Rifles, Pistols, to name a few. Want a sniper? No need to actually put any points in Coordination, the only thing that matters is the Sniper Rifle skill. But of course that character won't be able to hit a damned thing with an Assault Rifle or Pistol when he/she lacks the skill points. Horrible design choice, and completely illogical.Attributes won't play any role outside of combat, and your INT 1 character will have exactly the same things to say as your INT 8 or INT 10 character. CHA doesn't play a role in conversations either, but of course we do have some weirdly choses skills like Smart♥♥♥♥♥ Kiss♥♥♥♥♥and Hard♥♥♥♥♥for some extra choices during conversation. Simplicity is key, and developers certainly don't seem to want the players to have to try and/or think so of course these♥♥♥♥♥dialogue options will be visible and even provide you the information what rank in the skill you need. You can also switch character in the middle of conversation, for example to another which has this particular♥♥♥♥♥skill. These 'skills' really should have been character traits optionably selected during character creation.It would seem I am ranting on about attributes and skills, but in my opinion they're key in a good RPG game. Create a game that responds strongly to the attributes and skills of a particular character and you have a game where you can actually role play a particular type, and replay the game with a completely different one and getting different responses, results, options. There's nothing of the sort in Wasteland 2.Your actions have consequences? Please. I'm getting a bit tired of games (and reviewers) advertising this when all you get is some different slide show ending with narrative at the end of the game. During the game there are virtually no consequences outside of the narrow context, the situation, you happen to find yourself in right there and then.Consequences would be running out of fresh water when you opt to save Ag Center, and thus subsequentially have to deal with issues related to that. Similarly, running out of food when you go to Highpool. But what's to be expected in a game where you can top up your canteens with fresh water from an oasis in a heavily irradiated zone? Hilarious. Water does not play any role at all in this game and I really have no idea why the developers didn't just drop it completely. Personally I would have preferred a much more significant impact, but I fear that would simply be too much to ask.The Tiered progress on weapons, and weapon mechanics themselves, are another utter fail decision. Tiered progression means you will have blunt weapons (like a lead pipe) with higher Armor Penetration than a rifle for example. Right, makes perfect sense. Weapon damage is another one, where one 5.56 mm caliber Assault Rifle will do a lot more damage than another only because of that arbitrary Tier statistic. Weapon choices per Tier are basically limited to a lower AP usage, lower damage version and higher AP usage, higher damage version. Higher Tier means higher Armor Penetration, a flat number that is compared to the flat Armor Class number of the target. The game doesn't update appearances based on armor equiped, so it's entirely possible to run into a bare chested generic cannibal with Armor Class 10, meaning some very heavy (and expensive) Armor. With me already raises the question how a cannibal trying to survive out in the wastes even managed to obtain such an armor really... Mechanics are as simplified as this: If Armor Penetration is equal to or exceeds Armor Class the weapon does the normal range of damage. When Penetration is lower, damage is reduced based on following calculation: (Pen / Class) * 100%.The Director's Cut added some perks (based on skills only, nothing on attributes) and one for Assault Rifles is called 'Hollow Point' which hilariously adds +1 Armor Penetration. It's these details that just show how very littly thought and effort the developers put into this game. It's all bland, illogical and inconsequential.Combat itself is extremely boring and repetitive with barely any tactical options/variations. Adding 'crouch' to DC version really did noty change anything to that, especially since you can't move around crouched. Aimed shots provide a bit of variety but the penalties are a flat hard set one, regardless of attributes, skills, weapon and/or scopes used. I'd add more but I'm out of characters........"
