,Not Recommended,240760,34787777,Posted: 6 September,all,dejaime=D-Newbie,"This is a review for the DC version of the game.This game, for what it promises, is not even a shadow of what Fallout 1 and 2 were. Aside from the extreme RNG dependency, this game doesn't offer that much. Boring activate-this-object side quests, with little to no thinking required or a minimally decent story made most of this game feel empty and boring. Obvious character progression.Pros:- Individually interesting settlements- Big party that allows for one or two interesting combat encounters- Many companions available in the game- Difficulty levels (mostly affects combat)Cons:- Awful and unjustified performance (this game runs at 30 fps dropping down to 5 fps on the same computer I play The Witcher 3 at 30 fps 1% lows)- Never delivered on their mod-support promise (and probably never will)- Mindless boring quests that rarely require thinking or planning- Obvious and shallow character progression- Full of bugs, crashes, glitches- Gets stuck on loading screens (seems to be their ""top priority bug"" since 2014, according to dev's posts on forums)- Wildly incompatible character portraits that ruin the little immersion you can force yourself into as soon as you see an indian with a geisha portrait (really, why even bother including those?)In the end, this definitely didn't live up to its hype. It's a mediocre tactical RPG with a generic storyline, bland combat and a really shallow character system.This definitely doesn't even remind me of old Fallout games.Not worth half its price."
