,Recommended,240760,18085611,"Posted: 18 September, 2015",all,Jacob_Applehoof,"So it's been a while since I initially picked up Wasteland 2 on a whim. I'm not a stark supporter or against the idea of the game. I wasn't a kickstart supporter, nor was I one who got swept away in the hype before the game came out. Comeing back to the game, I've had time to mull over my choices, as well as the game in general. I believe, without a doubt, that this was one of the best RPG games I've ever played.Don't get me wrong, it's not open-ended or loose with the story. You can't just run around and do what you want. You are on rails with the story for most main segments of the game. Where it shines, however, is in just how powerful the game's willpower is in letting you choose what happens. Most games have their ""in order to get the best outcome, you have to do this"" situation that I always feel pushed towards. In Skyrim, for example, they always pushed you towards one side. If you were on the rebel's side, you were always pushed towards one stock ending for that story ark. Wasteland 2, weather by misfortune or by choice, allows your mistakes to shape the story. If you kill innosents along the way through saving a city, you'll most likely find the city upset about who you killed, or at least less happy about your intervention of their problem. It's not ""do X to get Y response"" but instead every X you have to do can yield various Y responces.This is the real way that Wasteland 2 shines. I do wish more morality issues came up that weren't isolated insodents. Many a time missions would either be ""large strings of missions with a resolution"" or ""little one-off missions"" and very little between it. It's a small gripe, as well as my wish for combat to be a tad easier at the start. This game really is a trial-by-fire game and causals won't find it easy.This game easily gets a 9.5/10 for me,  only lowered by the slight anoience I have when re-playing certain segments I wish were more open-ended."
