76561198040642365,Recommended,240760,23528216,"Posted: 12 June, 2016",all,Snootch,"This is a great game for turn-based RPG fans.  There is a ton of reading to do, as is required of the genre, but it nevertheless enables you to be a part of the story in ways that simple actions cannot.The character building seems to be a weakness in this game, primarily because the player will want to ""do everything,"" but spreading around Skill Points makes that desire very challenging.  Personally, I got frustrated when I couldn't ""do everything,"" such as be a ""Hard A s s,"" because I couldn't budget the Skill Points for it, but then that opportunity was over.  Not a game changer in the grand scheme of things, but again... I like to ""do everything.""The combat system for Wasteland 2 is about 50 times better than something like Shadowrun.  The percentage chances for hitting and missing in Wasteland 2 actually make some sense, and you will be properly rewarded or penalized for combat decisions you make.  Games in the same genre as Wasteland 2, like Shadowrun, have these super-frustrating ""random number generation"" combat systems where you will miss your targets so much so (even with 92% ""success chance"") that you will yell at the freaking video game developers when things are abundantly unfair or unpredictable.  Thus, Wasteland 2 is much more strategic and fun when you have a fairly certain understanding of the risks of your decisions.  Wasteland 2 is much more fair (whether you die or live) in the combat system than other games in the genre, and thus makes you want to play it longer and care more about the story and your characters, comparatively speaking.The other things I love about the combat system in Wasteland 2 are the abilities to (1) sort of ""sneak attack"" a bad guy (say, with your sniper) and get the fight started before they are ready, and (2) duck behind cover and increase your chances of survival (very similar to the XCOM combat system).  Given the fairness and strategic impacts of Wasteland 2's combat system, those alone have given me the ability to recommend this game to any fan of the genre.  (I do no recommend playing Shadowrun, which breaks my heart to say.)Really, XCOM and Wasteland will be your two primary turn-based, isometric RPGs that you will be playing on your computer for a long time to come."
