76561197969097267,Recommended,240760,17654587,"Posted: 21 August, 2015",all,Zero K,"I'm not normally the type to pre-order games, but I bought this one at $59.99 while it was in Early Access, which is basically preorder. Here's the short version of my review:I do not regret that decision.I have bought a whopping two pre-order games in the past 5 years. The other was XCOM: The Bureau, because I was comming off a high from XCOM: Enemy Unknown and forgot that a shooter-XCOM was a ♥♥♥♥ing stupid idea. For Wasteland 2 it was due to a combination of love for Fallout 1&2 and outside recommendations. Wasteland 2 did not disappoint. Mostly.If you liked Fallout 1 or 2, or never played them, give Wasteland 2 a shot. The story tone overall is dark, but it makes sure to lighten things up as you achieve goals, and there is a lot of hidden comedy to be found, adding a little bit of sillyness to the stark seriousness of the wastes. That might sound incongruous, but Brian Fargo's directing and his team's writing hold it together in a way that is sensical and digestible without becoming mundane. Events have weight and depth, and that weight gradually lifts as you succeed in goals, if only momentarily as the story progresses.My only complaints are in the combat system. It isn't bad by any means; throw a dart at a game listing and you'll hit something worse. It just seems to be lacking a bit compared to Fallout 2. Overall the leveling and combat system are a fair bit simplified from the Fallout games, which I dislike a bit; while there is something to be said for simplicity, Fallout was still on the friendly side of the line of where too much complexity becomes a chore rather than fun, if only just. I guess my main complaint is that it led to an odd situation where I completely avoided wearing armor throughout the entire game as if it where plague-ridden, whereas in the venerable Fallout if you weren't wearing Powered Armor by act 5 you'll just spontaneously explode. So maybe it's a petty complaint, but a complaint nonetheless. Maybe I should just be glad that was one in-game expense I could completely ignore.Other than that, it is a little difficult to believe that a character could be a master sniper and yet unable to hit the broadside of a barn if you hand them a shotgun, but what the hell, it's more combat focused than Fallout 1 or 2, so it is reasonable to expect the mechanical focus to shift towards combat, even if it does lead to some silly levels of specialization.In summary, there's a few petty gripes for the long-term Fallout fans, but much like Bethesda's work, this is overall a positive development in that vein. If you want a good post-apocalyptic story or a squad-based combat game, then look no further. It's not perfect, but it is quite good."
