76561197970490959,Recommended,240760,12182868,"Posted: 21 September, 2014",all,Third Wheel,"DISCLAIMER: I have not finished this game yet, but have put some solid hours into it.  The advertisement I saw claimed 80 hours of content and I'm pushing 24, so even if half of it is optional, I'm pretty well into it.  If not, then this is epic indeed and rivals or surpasses almost the entire Mass Effect trilogy by itself.Wasteland 2 is the sequel -- 25 years later -- to Wasteland, the RPG that first had us out exploring the post apocalyptic US.  This game oozes nostalgia.  When playing it, there are hints of the original CRPGs, the isometric views that we came to love so much through Fallout 1 & 2, Diablo 1 & 2 and on into Baldur's Gate and Icewind Dale.  Kudos go out to Brian Fargo and team who labored on this game:  it's deeply satisfying if you have the historic perspective to catch the bits of history have been worked into  the game.The plus side is that everything you wanted in a Wasteland sequel is here.  The bad news is that yep, there are skills and skill trees that represent the easiest, most complete path and you will not have all of those skills.  Too bad.  Either figure out another way of getting around the problems or get used to waiting for that quick load.  Funny story: I never actually finished the original game because I lacked the skills needed at one point, but had depopulated so much of the adversaries that I really just didn't want to go back and redo it all from scratch since just going up levels wasn't an option.  So, there's that, but additionally there are inventory quirks that leave you wondering if you really need some items or not, but that previous experience to the original games, and the oddball side quests for random stuff, make you paranoid about leaving anything.As for the quests, they're structured in the big scale so that choices have consequences and you cannot be the ultimate paragon of good.  It's just not possible, which makes sense as well as adds a certain replayability to the game.  The only gameplay complaint that isn't tempered by nostalgia is the frequency of random animal/raider encounters on world-map travel.  It's a bit high and while it's easy experience points, it's also kind of annoying that you can't gracefully evade the encounters all the time.The sound is good, but not stunning and some of the voice acting is amateurish, but the sheer amount of voice acting and the ambience it brings to the game is worthwhile.  I was actually mildly disappointed when I got to various dialog that wasn't voiced, to be honest.  When creating characters, I have to admit I was skeptical about how good the game itself would look.  Since the characters are 3d models and the expectation is that you'll be zoomed out most of the time, I have to say it looks great.  All of the annoyances of isometric games are still there, but you can rotate the camera to show hidden items when you want to, so that helps in cases of hidden items, problematic pathfinding, or even combat targeting.  Yet, these are problems we've seen so many times that honestly, they kind of fade into the background.  The only persistent annoyance with the graphics is the camera's rotation and how it will rotate only 10 degrees or so at a time with mandatory slowdowns.  I'm not sure what that's about, but I got over it pretty quickly and it also faded from my brainspace while playing.  Overall, the game is pleasing to look at and the Unity Engine has my respect for what they've been able to accomplish with it.The tone of the original game is captured pretty well.  It's less gritty/hardcore than fallout, but only in that it pokes some fun at itself and the genre directly in the dialog, story, and background whereas Fallout sort of says absurd things happened and here's what you're dealing with as a result.  Do not take this to mean it's a silly game.  There are very dark moments, hard choices, and many opportunities to be hero or villain.  Also, there's a lot of profanity.  I'm not offended, but if you've got small kids, then get the headphones out... or not.Bottom line on this game is that you will truly enjoy this if you are looking for a successor to Fallout 1 & 2 and didn't like the decision to go FPS/3rd person over-the-shoulder camera OR if you are old enough to actually remember the first game and have played PC CRPGS for decades.  For others who enjoy the idea of being a ranger on the radiation frontier, it's a blast and worth your time."
