,Recommended,240760,13501628,"Posted: 21 December, 2014",all,MilesVorkosigan,"Overall this is a good game.  As long as you're aware of what game it's trying to be you should enjoy it.Wasteland 2 plays like a slightly less polished Fallout 2, but with a Wasteland setting (rougher and with less 60's nostalgia humor).  The gameplay is a throwback to the original western cRPGs; it's a cold RNG hell mitigated only by extensive save scumming.Graphically it's a 3/4 down perspective 2.5D experience.  Unlike Fallout 2, the worlds aren't 2D drawings but are rather 3D rendered.  This is nice because it allows the camera view to be rotated between the 4 cardinal compass directions.  But, it adds the negative ""feature"" that sometimes important things (like loot or enemys) are obscured by the terrain, forcing you to constantly rotate the camera view to ensure you're not missing something.  It's also quite low res, especially in the character model department.For what parts I've gotten through, the story is interesting and has numerous tie-ins to the original Wasteland storey.  But, it has enough explanation that people that didn't play (or can't remember anymore) the original Wasteland won't feel lost.  The game also alows you many different ways to complete most quests from diplomatic to violent and from good to bad.So, as long as you don't mind reloading a lot (save early and often!) it's quite a fun trip back in memory lane.  This is very much how old school cRPGs were.  And, it's a blast!"
,Recommended,240760,13514234,"Posted: 21 December, 2014",all,CryO5,"This is the closest you'll come to an old-school Fallout game (specifically 1 & 2). This game contains a large amount of customization, an excellent combat system, and a good 90+ hours of gameplay per playthrough, making it more bang for your buck than most games out there.However, before you buy, know that this game requires a bit more patience than what you may be used to in modern games. There is a decent amount of team management, dialogue/text to investigate and pay attention to, and the tactical combat can sometimes take up to fifteen minutes to finish a single fight sequence.The developers have also gone to great lengths to prevent you from creating a perfect playthrough for your team, as well as savescumming. For many post-apocalyptic enthusiasts, these are very good things, but they're not for everyone.At the time of writing this review, I also noticed a decent handful of bugs (nothing totally game-breaking though) and a lack of polish in a few aspects of the game. It's extremely impressive though considering the small team that developed it, as well as the amount of content for the price.In short, this can be a very challenging game, but extremely rewarding. It's a definite recommend for anyone looking for a game that respects their intelligence and abstains from holding their hand. If you're someone who enjoys taking their time, doesn't fault an extremely complex game for having a few bugs, and doesn't mind seeing several hopelessly dark twists in a single story, you'll find a gem in Wasteland 2."
