,Recommended,240760,12424140,"Posted: 9 October, 2014",all,WraithKind,"If you like fallout, fallout 2, or fallout tactics, you'll enjoy this game.  Set in a post apocalyptic world with limited resources, there is an emphasis on creating a diverse, yet focused, skill set among your initial team members, as well as recruiting needed skill sets from among the npc's you encounter along the way.  There's a surprising, and welcome, amount of choice and consequence, and often those consequences aren't felt until later in the game.  There are so many ways to play through the game, and so many different choices, it is easy to see that this game can easily be played through multiple times with different experiences.Graphically, the unity engine delivers the needed aesthetics.  While the ui is solid, it sometimes does not quite flow the way you'd expect, but once you figure it out, you should be fine.  I would point out, however, that if you are a mouse clicker, and not one to use keyboard shortcuts, this game will definitely wear out your hands.  If you are an older gamer  (like I am), this could be a problem....I've learned to use my keyboard shortcuts.The story is solidly written, and you can tell the developers and designers had fun putting this all together.  There are more than a few moments in the game that gave me a good laugh, and caused me to shake my head.  Some of the references in even the type of loot you can pick up made me laugh (I'm thinking of you, ""bat♥♥♥♥♥♥quot;, lol)The combat is a whole bunch of turn-based goodness.  Though not quite as varied as, say, Divinity: Original Sin, it makes intelligent use of the cover concept, and emphasizes tactics over ""jumping in"".  This portion of the game reminded me a lot of Fallout: Tactics (with turn-based: individual turned on), in this regard.  You also had to watch your ammo expenditure, and constantly evaluate whether or not the enemies you faced was worth the ammo, since ammo is a rare commodity - espeically for sniper rifles!  This is where your 'brawlers' become important.  Also, let's not forget weapon smithing.  This was a layer on combat that added a little extra spice, and I personally didnt' realize to what extent I could use this skill.  Weapon smithing definitely defines the concept of ""success is when perparation meets opportunity."" A sniper that doesn't jam and has longer range? Yes please.  A bladed weapon that is easier to swing, letting you swing it more often? No question.  These little differences have often been the difference of a battle in which i use way too many trauma kits (lol), and a solid win with using a some pain killers along the way.Though the game was fun, like every game, it had its flaws.  My main issue with the game is that, while I enjoyed the 'old-school gamer' vibe, it should have brought a few more modern gameplay elements in.  For example, if you have a character in your party that has safecracking skill, and there's a safe, don't make me select that character, then activate their safecracking skill, and then click on the safe.  Instead, I would expect a little more intelligence from my game. When I hover over the safe (assuming its not trapped), my icon should change to the safecracking icon, and then the character in my party with the highest safecracking skill should automatically make the attempt.  Fewer clicks, and the immersion isn't necessarily broken because I already know who my 'safecracker' is!In summary, this is a fun game full of choice, consequence, and quirky humor.  The turn based combat is pretty solid, with a respectable variety of enemies which you have to face.  ""Old-school"" gamers will like this game, and even some younger gamers who want to see what all us old farts miss from the days of yore.  Give it a shot, you might be surprised!"
