,Recommended,240760,12271743,"Posted: 27 September, 2014",all,gabensparklebeard.jpg,"Once, long ago, I played a game called Wasteland that forever changed how I would view the way games should be played.  It was the basis by which many other post-apocalyptic titles (such as Fallout) and essentially solidified the turn-based strategy genre.  Playing Wasteland now, years and years from when it was first published, is a frustrating experience; but nonetheless, I still feel a little of the magic I felt back then as a kid playing something that was so cool and so new for its time.Wasteland 2 does not disappoint.  I will readily admit I'm the type of player that hypes himself up too much before his first minutes in a game and leaves disappointed because the experience did not coincide with his images of it.  However, given a few hours of effort and attempts, I find that Wasteland 2 is a deeply satisfying sequel to one of my favorite games of ages past.For those unfamiliar with old-style turn-based games, this game is DIFFICULT.  You will not be a battle that you don't have the potential to lose.  Even the most soft of the game modes is has some extremely difficult battles in them.  Chance can and does fail you.  That chest which probably has some decent loot more often than not will be permanently broken instead of opening for you.  Your gun will jam at the most inopportune times and a number of enemies will be sufficiently higher level than you to make your first couple of fights in each new map be an extremely cautious experience.  You will be required to use all of the skills available to you to effectively fight battles.  In higher difficulties, it is highly possible to design a character that is completely unusable past a certain point in the game.  Not to mention your characters are capable of being permanently dead.  Resources are limited and you'll find times when you run out of ammo (make sure you bring spare weapons).   However, if challenge suits you, this is the type of game you should play.  The musical score is very well thought out and after a few hours the story becomes very engaging.Some problems, like most reviews I've read, have more to do with nitpicking bugs or GUI designs instead of something that is truly gamebreaking or experience ruining.  The graphics are awful for the current generation of games, but the environments are well thought out enough to really ignore that type of problem;  besides, as one review pointed out, if you're playing this game you aren't playing it because it's pretty.Other issues include complicated inventory management, the inability to adequately group characters (there are several points in the game where you have to break up your team to manage certain areas) and a 'sluggish' interface (usually due to abundantly clicking a certain NPC or area).  Additionally I was disappointed that the voiceovers were pretty limited, usually first lines of a dialog, but to be honest I got over that pretty quickly once I settled back into my old-school RPG mood.  One really delightful element to the game is that I feel that each skill tree is actually worth investing in, even if some are more influential than others.  I don't feel like another round of Diablo where there are 3 specific builds worth doing and everything else is trash.  If you play, I highly recommend diversifying your skill sets (stick to roughly 4-5 per characters, exceeding that you'll become a jack of all trades and a master of none) and get close to maxing your intelligence (skill points per level are awarded based on int, 8 for 4 points, 10 for 5).All in all I would rate it an 8 out of 10, most of my complaints are polish and general clunkiness.  But, as expected, I found no lack of enjoyment thus far in engaging in the post-apocalyptic world of southwest Arizona, a member of the Desert Rangers once more."
