,Recommended,240760,12376130,"Posted: 5 October, 2014",all,DustyKnives,"TL;DRBugs aside, one of the best games I've ever played. Combat of XCOM meets the post-apocalyptic style of Fallout, with great writing all around and quirky humor sprinkled around serious themes. Worth $60? Definitely. 9.5/10OVERVIEWI just finished the game the night before this review, and after putting 27 hours between multiple playthroughs into the beta, I kinda zipped through the first half of the game since I knew what to expect. Still, it took 30 hours to finish the game, and because of the amount of content I realize I missed, it should have taken much longer.REPLAY VALUE: 9/10There is a ton of replay value. Often, you are told to choose between sides, whether to save one base vs the other, or keep the current ruling party in power vs replacing them. Sometimes you can negotiate something where everybody wins. Other times, I turned both sides into a bloodbath and skipped away with all of their valuables. After finishing this review, I intend to start a whole new party and go through it again to see how different actions will affect the outcome.STORY: 8/10While predictable at times, it was still fun to see how things unfold. Each of the settlements has its own share of problems, ranging from the absurd (giant killer plants attacking us!!) to the exciting (paramilitary team trying to tactfully usurp power from religious wackjobs). While the ending wasn't mindblowing, it was satsifying.GAMEPLAY: 9.5/10There are so very many ways to solve problems. At first, the number of skills seems overwhelming, since you only have a limited number of characters to learn them. But if my lockpicker can't open a door, maybe I can have my strength build kick it down. He fractured his leg on it? Hell, let's just blow it off the hinges. Where's that guy with the RPG? Exploring the world is exciting as well. There are plenty of areas that will never get mentioned if you only follow the main storylines, so many hidden caches of weapons to stumble upon. And there's nothing more exciting than going into combat with a brand new shiny weapon. Speaking of which...COMBAT: 9/10The combat system is the turn-based strategic grid style that XCOM and Fallouts 1/2/Tactics used. Command your sniper to climb that ladder and watch her accuracy - and damage output - triple. Hide your SMGer behind a wall and order him to ambush anyone who walks by. Why should he walk into harm's way? Put your assault people behind the wrecked car for cover and an accuracy bonus. Doesn't always work, since enemies will still use flanking maneuvers, grenades, and the same tactics as you. If you fall, you'd better hope your surgeon can come fix you before you bleed out. If you're about to fall, send your medic for a quick patchup.PROBLEMS:There are a lot of bugs in the second half of the game. For those of us who played it while it was in the Early Access stage, the second half of the game was not available, so once you reach that point, expect typos, a few conversations without purpose, people appearing in two places at once, etc. I personally haven't experienced anything gamebreaking, just frustrating, but the team has been hard at work polishing the game since release."
