,Recommended,240760,12380276,"Posted: 5 October, 2014",all,thewhistles,"Highly recommended if you miss playing Fallout 2, Baldur's Gate, and other iso-view classics. Wasteland 2 has a ton of quests and many of them have repurcussions depending on your choices. Character building is tough because there are more skills than you can master, so it's better to forget about trying to max out in everything.The dialogue and writing is very extensive and humorous. Arizona is filled with weird characters and location descriptions. Environments are large and it's easy to miss boxes and vaults hidden away in corners. This is the type of game where you have to back track in order to loot and explore everything.Combat is good enough for what it is, but could eventually become a chore. Other than move, attack, switch weapons, and switch firing types, your only other options are to crouch or headshot. Headshot seems pointless because it's -40% chance to hit, 200% damage, and 0% critical. 0% critical for a headshot? My sniper character has a 25% critical chance, so it's a tradeoff that doesn't seem to be worth it.Switching items in your inventory and hands doesn't cost any action points, but a ""quick belt"" for grenades and such would seem handy. Also, weapons jam too much. They SAY the percentages are usually 2-4%, but I would guess they're more around 6-10%.Weaknesses aside, this is an awesome game with a lot to do. Even right at the beginning is a large decision which affects the later game. I expect replay value will be very high for me."
