,Recommended,240760,12465604,"Posted: 12 October, 2014",all,rpdillon,"Wasteland 2 is a great game.  It's an open-world RPG with tactical turn-based combat.  Many players that enjoy it played Wasteland (from 1988!) though I never have.  Nevertheless, Wasteland 2 has been well worth my money and time.  The post-apocalyptic theme is appealing, and the attention to the writing gives a welcome bit a variety in a game that is dominated by turn-based combat and map exploration.  Even if you're not familiar with Wasteland, Wasteland 2 carries on the tradition of the Fallout series (albeit less tongue-in-cheek), which more players will be familiar with.One caveat: I'm playing Wasteland 2 on two different Linux machines (both 64-bit Ubuntu), one on AMD Radeon and the other on Nvidia.  There are notable stability issues in Wasteland that force a reboot on both machines, making long play sessions frustrating.  There are some threads about it in the forums, so I'm hoping the developers will track it down within a few weeks, because it's truly great that they  decided to bring such a great game to Linux in the first place."
,Recommended,240760,12264419,"Posted: 27 September, 2014",all,.o0O0o.,"I just made MY FIRST Wasteland 2 starter group! I took a few hours on the profiles. When the intro movie was playing, I thought of a change, and cancelled the game without saving my place. None of the customized characters were reselectable upon restart. Be careful.The ideal WL2 group configuration is to go with skill groupings primarily  and stats based on skills. In other words, one or two knowlegists (breaking things and making things), one or two weaponists (CloseRange/LongRange, HighAmmo/LowAmmo, SameAmmo/DifferentAmmo), and one or two generalists (peaceful NPS interaction and violent NPC interaction)You can distribute the skills between party members so that the loss or replacement of one member isn't catastrophic. Just as you would want at least three members to be armed with unique weapon types, you would want each member to have a dash of general and knowledge skills. E.G., One person to disarm the trap on the object, one person to disable the alarm on the object, one person to pick the lock on the object, and one person to crack the safe on the object.Area 1 Tips:-Mike Scott is on one of the grave markers, for all you CS Horns out there. Pretend to leave some candy on his marker.- Don't use dig the graves, save, load from before, then dig again, or the item quality goes down permanently. There is a non-random item-class punishment seed generator, which can be abused on netbooks by other players with shared controls and console switching and screen feeding, a la Twitch. Energy cells and utilitarian items on the first dig turned into dirt-junk rings on the second dig. I'm not sure if this is one of those games where you can combine items in your inventory to make new items. I did not try putting things INTO the grave, becauase I don't know if everything is treated as a container. I am a bad person...-You can talk the doorman just NE of the gravesite with one of the verbal skills to get a 