76561198035964670,Recommended,240760,12711353,"Posted: 31 October, 2014",all,Mr. Can Do,"This game provides the real feeling of despair when you lose a friend. I first began my adventure on the hardest difficulty thinking, ""hey I can easily win this"". Two days into the game and I am here with half a squad of rangers, the others dead from a series of grenades, landmines, rocket launchers, bullets, and bad luck. It got to the point where I felt like loading my re-saves to attempt saving them. I quickly realized however that I enjoyed the game more when it was challenging and not easy. For this reason I am continuing forward within my adventure.The pros of this game are very numerous:FIRST OFF, THEIR IS NO DLC CONTENT (This is a pro for me because the game has all the content intended within it)HOURS OF GAMEPLAY (we are not talking about an hour of gameplay here people, It took me 55 hours of gameplay to make me realize that I am about half way done).DIFFICULTY SETTINGS (This option allows you make the game easier or tougher at certain parts throughout the game. This can help the user either complete the game early if they enjoy finishing the game quickly or long if they want to savor agonizing defeat).CUSTOMIZATION (The option to customize the appearance of the soldiers within your squad helps in creating a unique group that you see fit in destroying the ranger's enemies. Saving the character template is also available so in the event that the player begins a new game. Basically, you can load an old character you created).STORYLINE (The storyline is amazing within my opinion, there are numerous side quests and main quests but they tie in perfectly together. For example, a side quest might even have a side quest within it! So it gives you more options in obtaining a different experience).Environment (The skills you pick within the game will determine how to deal with certain situations.  Let’s say that your squad stumble upon a locked safe. Nobody in your squad is a safecracker so you have no idea what to do. You can either ignore the safe for later or do what I do and blow it up with some good old TNT. Maybe a pipe bomb or grenade for the tougher ones though. Though last time I used a grenade it ended up blowing up the safe and its contents, so be careful with that. Anyhow, the point I'm making is that the game experience will reflect upon the skills within the squad).EASTER EGGS: (Remember in good old halo days or other video games where the developers added something and you would say something along the lines of, ""that shouldn't be here, but damn is it funny"". The game provides exactly that with multiple references to certain lines and items you encounter. So enjoy and good luck finding them).VALUE: (Though the game may appear to be high in price within first look. The true value of the game comes from the experience you will get from it. Not all video games are created with as many features as Wasteland 2. It is for this reason that I would highly recommend it to anyone in search of a fun game with lots of hours of gameplay).Cons: A few minor bugs here and there but that is expected within most games and it does severely hinder the experience of the gameplay."
,Recommended,240760,12753527,"Posted: 2 November, 2014",all,Burnaboy,"A wonderful throwback to the glory days of PC gaming when isometric adventures were king. Though not as open world exploration-friendly as I would have liked, as most locations are destinations you're told to go to for the story rather than discovering on your own, it has a great way of making every decision you make in game have consequences, good or bad, that make each playthrough unique."
76561197985151938,Recommended,240760,12755688,"Posted: 2 November, 2014",all,centipedia,"Writing is the most important part of a role playing game like this, and the writing in Wasteland 2 is quite good (although a little shy of greatness). The world feels big and rich, and you feel as if you have quite a bit of freedom. The game mechanics are good and feel fair, although there are a few important things that are by no means intuitive. (For example, anything that comes out of a toaster will be a minor or major plot point and clothing, despite having detailed inventory slots, is entirely cosmetic with no in-game impact.) The user interface is pretty good, although one could make some nitpicks. Sound is handled quite well and this is one of the very few games where I never felt the urge to turn the music off, despite playing for 100 hours. Graphics are never a high priority in this type of game, and while Wasteland graphics are state of the art for the genre they would be someone primitive looking in other contexts. I have to say the art one area where the game really falls down because, despite looking quite good most of the time, there just wasn't enough of it to do what the game was trying to do. Hand painted images rarely matched descriptions which rarely matched 3D avatars, often to bewildering effect. Paintings would have the wrong hair color, build, clothing, and race. 3D avatars would sometimes even be the wrong gender. Surprisingly, this level of mismatch even extends to the player character images. Few character paintings have 3D avatars available that even vaguely match. Even more disconcertingly, the low number of paintings means that they are re-used many times in game so you will occasionally come across an NPC using your character's portrait.But all in all, this is a very impressive game, easily worth its full, original sale price. I personally feel it is a seminal work, which will be referenced for decades."
