76561198006029791,Recommended,240760,12470914,"Posted: 12 October, 2014",all,Greymalkin,"Finished.  Damonta hates me.But I love this game.  So will be going back to save those people another day.Wasteland 2 has hit that magical spot of being a nostalgia game that is much more than its heritage and requires no knowledge of his history for a new player to get into it.First and foremost in its achievements is the story, something oft lacking in games (of any generation) and more importantly the story is coherent and makes sense within its own universe without falling into stupidity or badly contradicting itself *cough*masseffect*cough*.  You can properly immerse yourself into the lives and motivations of the people around you.Gameplay is uncomplicated but solid, and even after you have mastered the art of making money and buying the best gear there will be combats which can challenge you.  Of course as in any good game, combat is always the side dish with the real challenge coming in surviving the wasteland and its problems.  A combat wombat specced team will be able to shoot their way through most of the game but will miss half the dialogue and die on a mine they didn't spot.  (Seriously spec  your main character to be good at demolitions.)This is where the team mechanic shines, you are no ubermensch of Skyrim who can be the best at everything and solo Fus-Ro-Dah your way through any challange, your medic, your rogue and your sniper will all have their moment in the sun.  Even the stats matter more than in most games, Intelligence is clearly the best, but scrimp too much on strength and that sweet minigun you could have sold for top dollar in town is going to have to be left behind and even though skills can improve vastly over the course of the game, you will likely only get 3-4 single stat point increases from go to whoa.In short, a definite thumbs up, go buy this game now and not out of some blind support of indi games but because this genuinely is a good quality, well considered, and entertaining game which while technically a sequel is so far beyond its predecessor as to stand entirely on its own."
